<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Be Important Contributor to World IT Industry: Intel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China's importance as a computer
manufacturer and consumer is growing, said visiting Chairman and
CEO of Intel Corp. Andrew Grove, here today.
</P>
<P>
He also said that China "will be an important contributor to
the world IT (information technology) industry."
</P>
<P>
The 63-year old leader of the world's largest chip producer
made the remarks at a news conference on Intel's latest China
plans after his meetings with Chinese officials including
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
The company will set up the Intel China Research Center in
Beijing within the first half of the year. The investment is
expected to be 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The operation of the center will be part of Intel's annual 2.8
billion dollar world-wide research and development efforts,
according to Grove.
</P>
<P>
The center will report to Intel headquarters located in Santa
Clara, California, Grove said, and it is set to explore
Internet-related issues and information technology disciplines
such as speech recognition that have particular relevance to
Chinese applications.
</P>
<P>
It is Intel second large R&AMP;D institute following the company's
software lab in Shanghai which works closely with China's software
developers.
</P>
<P>
Grove also told the press that Intel's first manufacturing
business in China already started operation, four months ahead of
schedule.
</P>
<P>
The operation is located in Shanghai, and costed 198 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say the rapid growth of China's computer
market helped attract investment and attention from major IT
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Intel officials say Grove will attend the ceremony marking the
birth of the 1 millionth computers manufactured by Legend Group,
China's largest computer producer.
</P>
<P>
At today's news conference, Grove also announced Intel will
provide 1.5 million yuan worth of 350 MHz and 400 MHz Pentium II
processor-based development systems to leading Chinese software
developers to assist the growth of the country's software sector.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Intel has 12 locations around China.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest projection of Intel, China will be the
second largest computer market in the world next to the United
States early next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
