<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing University Host Nobel Prize Winners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Beijing University, one of China's
most prestigious universities, is currently witnessing
enthusiastic celebrations marking the centennial anniversary of
its establishment.
</P>
<P>
Nobel Prize winner Chen Ning Yang was delayed for half hour
this moring in a traffic jam while on his way to attend
celebration activities.
</P>
<P>
Professor Yang arrived in Beijing after a long journey from New
York and appeared before a group of admiring university students
today.
</P>
<P>
"I was familiar with the Beijing University (Beida) campus some
60 years ago," said the 76-year-old Yang. "I used to ice skate on
Weiming Lake in the winter."
</P>
<P>
"Alumni from around the world have witnessed the university's
great achievements, with young students of today indicating their
bright future," said Yang, who graduated from Southwest Associated
University consisting of Peking (Beijing), Tsinghua and Nankai
universities in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
Professor Yang, who shared the Nobel Prize in Physics with his
colleague Trung Dao Lee in 1957, inspired the young listeners with
his speech about "balance and physics". A large number of students
sat on the floor a the lecture hall which was filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
Steven Chu, the 1997 winner of the Nobel Prize in Physics,
presented a speech on the "Atomic and the Molecular Physics on the
New Frontier Towards Unification with Biology". Chu, 55, is an
honorary professor at Beijing University and head of the physics
department at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Tseh Lee, winner of a Nobel Prize in Chemistry, talked
about the challenges of the coming 21st century. Lee responded to
a question concerning why scientists from China's interior
areas have not won get Nobel prizes by noting, "It's not really
not important to win the Nobel Prize itself."
</P>
<P>
"The development of science requires a good environment. China
is improving its scientific environment," said Lee, the current
president of Academia Sinica in Taiwan,
</P>
<P>
Shing-tung Yau, a Harvard professor of math, presented
the final speech to end the half day academic festival. Yau won
the Fields Medal, the highest international award for mathematics
in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
