<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ottawa to Halt Lake Water Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is
investigating legal means to halt an Ontario company's bid to
export fresh water from Lake Superior to Asia, reports said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy voiced his strong
opposition to the proposed water export, which has been approved
by Ontario provincial environment ministry.
</P>
<P>
"We are now examining various pieces of legislation ... to
determine if there is some form of prevention that can be
applied," Axworthy was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"What we are looking at is the real question of the large-scale
export of fresh water, which we certainly have always taken a
strong stand against," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is a matter of some real concern, and we're looking at some
of the options that we have," the minister told the parliament on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nova Group, a company based in the city of Sault Ste. Mario on
the eastern tip of the lake, has won a first-ever permit from the
Ontario provincial government to export water from Lake Superior
to Asia.
</P>
<P>
With the permit, the company hopes to take up to 600 million
liters of water a year for the next five years from the lake for
shipping abroad.
</P>
<P>
Though the amount is "reasonably small" compared to the normal
flow of water out of the lake, the action could set a precedent
and encourage companies from Canada and the United States to draw
on limited fresh water resources for profit, Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
"If one entrepreneur decides to do it and get away with it,
then others will be encouraged to follow, then you have a serious
problem," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The provincial environment ministry granted the export permit
on the grounds that the company had demonstrated the project would
result in no significant environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
The permit has led to a U.S. government official saying that
Washington is concerned the exports could violate a 1909 treaty
which established joint Canada-U.S. management of the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
So far, Nova Group said it has not arranged any sales yet. The
permit will allow it conduct feasibility studies and attract
potential investors.
</P>
<P>
"There is a need for water in the Asia market," Nova president
John Febbraro said. Selling water there was "worth a shot".
</P>
<P>
The water from Lake Superior, the cleanest of the Great Lakes,
is believed to have a market in Asia because the region is often
plagued by water shortages, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
