<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM Defends France's Role in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine
Tuesday strongly defended the role played by France in Rwanda
before and during the 1994 genocide committed against the Tutsi
minority by the Hutu majority in that country.
</P>
<P>
During a hearing held by the special commission of the National
Assembly investigating the French role in Rwanda from 1990 to
1994, Vedrine said that France had worked with "tenacity" to
prevent the genocide from taking place.
</P>
<P>
"The French policy, rightly or wrongly, was based on the idea
that one should absolutely attain a political agreement (in
Rwanda)... But unfortunately, we only succeeded in delaying the
violences," he said.
</P>
<P>
When the genocide in Rwanda took place, Vedrine was the
secretary general of President Francois Mitterrand, who had a
semi-secretive presidential staff specialized in African affairs.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine admitted that France was trying to help the regime of
Rwandan President Juvenal Habyarimana to fend off attacks from the
Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front, which invaded from Uganda.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, Paris was pressuring Habyarimana to
accept a sharing of power with the Tutsi minority, he said.
</P>
<P>
Habyarimana was killed on April 6, 1994, when the French
military helicopter carrying him and his Burundian counterpart,
Cyprien Ntaryamira, was shot down by a missile over Kigali, the
capital of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
His death immediately triggered the massacres of Tutsis and
moderate Hutus by Hutu militias backed by troops.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that on the eve of his death, Habyarimana had
accepted French proposal that Hutu extremists be excluded from his
government.
</P>
<P>
The Hutu extremists were exasperated by the attitude of France,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine refused to speculate on who shot down the helicopter of
Habyarimana, saying that it could either be done by Hutu
extremists or the Rwandan Patriotic Front which he said was trying
to take over power from the Hutus.
</P>
<P>
He said that on the Soviet-made SA-16 missile which shot down
the helicopter, the registration numbers were incomplete so one
cannot say from where it came from.
</P>
<P>
As for the role played by the United States in central Africa
at that time, Vedrine said that Washington was supporting Uganda
in order to contain its neighbor Sudan, which the Americans
accused of supporting terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
