<HEADLINE> Egypt: Group-15 Summit to Promote South-North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said on Monday that the upcoming
summit meeting of the Group-15 in Cairo is aimed at leading
developing countries to constructive dialog with developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters that the
summit due on 11-13 will afford opportunities to the member states
to take stock of the recent developments of the world economy and
formulate a unified stand on global economic order.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda of the summit are political and economic
issues including Asian countries' financial crisis, cooperation
between the group's members and activating North-South dialog, he
added.
</P>
<P>
As a group of developing countries from Latin America, Africa
and Asia, the G-15, which was founded in 1989, comprises Egypt,
India, Indonesia, Malaysia, Yugoslavia, Algeria, Zimbabwe,
Senegal, Nigeria, Argentina, Jamaica, Venezuela, Mexico, Brazil,
Peru, Chile and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Seven heads of state, three vice presidents and a number of
ministers are expected to attend the summit, in which they will
issue a communique spelling out the stances of the group on
economic and political issues.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the summit, trade ministers and foreign
ministers of the G-15 will convene their separate meetings here
this week.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members, with 30 percent of the world's population and
27 percent of the land area of the third world, represent the
emerging economies of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
The total gross domestic product of the G-15 constitutes 39
percent of the third world and exports account for 31 percent of
the developing countries' total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
