<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Records Fewer Prison Escapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The number of escapes from South
African prisons had dropped from an average of 100 a month last year
to 40 a month at present, Correctional Services Minister Sipo Mzimela
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a parliamentary debate on his budget vote, Mzimela
said the drop in escapes followed the introduction of anti-corruption
measures and the installation of electric fences on prison perimeters,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped that this signified the end of escapes in the not
too distant future.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 4,200 prisoners escaped from South Africa's prisons. The
escapes of some of the country's most wanted and dangerous criminals
sparked widespread public furore.
</P>
<P>
Later study showed the majority of the breaks could be attributed
to negligence of police officials. Other problems included
over-population of cells and poor facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
