<HEADLINE> Romanian PM on Bid for OECD Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Romania can assume all the
obligations incumbent on it as possible future member of the
Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD),
Romanian Prime Minister Radu Vasile told a press conference on
Tuesday held for the official launch of an OECD study on Romania.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Prime Minister hoped that the economic study on
Romania, the first in-depth analysis of the country by the
Organisation in line with its other studies on its memebr
countries, would show a certain priority for Romania.
</P>
<P>
Vasile said that Romania wanted to widen its relations with the
organisation with a view to becoming OECD member. "The admission
of Romania will strengthen the economic potential in Central
Europe, together with Hungary, the Czech Republic, Poland - all
three OECD members, and with Slovakia, another possible future
member," stressed the Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
Romania tendered in March 1995 an official request to OECD to
be admitted as observer to three committees of the Organisation,
namely trade, commerce and sea transport. 
</P>
