<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Preconditions for Peace Negotiations in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. envoy said here Tuesday that
there should be no preconditions for peace negotiations by either
side in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Cyprus President
Glafcos Clerides, U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel said that "I think that is one of the fundamental rules
of negotiations: that there should be no preconditions."
</P>
<P>
He said that his meeting with Clerides focused on the visit of
U.S. presidential emissary Richard Holbrooke and "what emerged by
all that."
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke wound up his three-day visit to Cyprus Monday, but he
failed in his attempt to resume the stalled intercommunal dialog
after intensive talks with the two communities' leaders on the
island.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the results of Holbrooke's visit, Feissel
said that the U.S. envoy himself admitted that he was not able to
move things forward "so we are still basically where we were and
where we have been for some time."
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, this is not good. We have been in an impasse and
the political situation has been getting worse, more difficult
and of course it is very important that we find a way to move
forward, because this is the only way that we can reach a
settlement," the U.N. envoy said.
</P>
<P>
Feissel stressed that it is in the interest of the parties
involved in the Cyprus issue to find a settlement to this problem
without delay. Otherwise, he warned that there would be negative
developments for the parties and the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and other parties involved have been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island in a bizonal and bicommunal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
