<HEADLINE> African Telecom Show Symbol of Revival: Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Africa Telecom '98, the
largest gathering of telecommunication experts and equipment in
Africa, symbolizes a spirit of revival and re-awakening
throughout the continent, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
His message was read by Egyptian ambassador to South Africa at
a forum running parallel with the telecommunications exhibition
opened Monday in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of the world's top telecommunication companies and
dozens of ministers from around the world attended the six-day
event.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said in his message that African nations are
determined to rise to the challenge of modernization without
detracting from its people's heritage.
</P>
<P>
"We will spare no effort in order to equip our new generations
with the knowledge and tools necessary to meet the challenges
that will face them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications is gaining an ever-growing importance in
people's new way of life, he said. "It is becoming one of the
main contributors to economic growth and a major tool for the
promotion of trade and investment."
</P>
<P>
Although African nations have make tangible progress in growth
and development in the past few years, they have fully realized
that much remains to be done to meet the people's increasing
needs and aspirations, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications show is a fitting occasion to crown the
achievements and to signal the beginning of a new era where
African nations will stand among nations of the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the challenges are beyond the means of any of the
countries in Africa individually, but well within the resources
of nations acting together.
</P>
<P>
New structures are being developed to try to pool resources
together to meet telecommunication demands which an individual
country can not meet with its national budget, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
