<HEADLINE> Arab Financial Institutions to Meet in Beirut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 bankers and economists
from the Arab and international institutions are expected to meet
here Wednesday to attend the 27th Arab Financial Institutions
Conference, the country's National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Also among the participants are 25 finance, economy and
planning ministers and 14 governors of central banks from Arab
countries as well as representatives of Arab and international
funds and financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
The agency said this is the second time for Lebanon to host the
annual conference, indicating it has restored its financial and
economic role in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon first held the conference in 1973 two years before the
country was plunged into a 15-year-long civil war.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day conference, participants will mainly discuss
 the challenges the Arab financial market will face in the next
century, economic reforms in Arab countries, lessons obtained from
the current Asian financial crisis and its impact on Arab economy.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also focus on Arab stock and bonds market
and the investment opportunities in Egypt and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The agency said Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri will
attend the meeting and made the opening speech. 
