<HEADLINE> Arab League: Lockerbie Victim Families Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Cairo-based Arab League (AL) said
Tuesday the families of the British victims in Lockerbie air
bombing support the Arab stance on quickly ending the tangle over
the trial of two Libyan suspects.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid said he got the message
of support in a letter from Jim Swire, spokesman for the British
families.
</P>
<P>
Also in the letter was the text of a message Swire sent to
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook on the outcome of his recent
talks with both Abdul-Meguid and Libyan officials.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with the League's permanent delegates,
Abdul-Meguid said the families in their message to Cook expressed
their support of the Arab undertaking to resolve the long-standing
Libya-West crisis and called on London to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sanctions were imposed on Libya in 1992 in response to
Tripoli's refusal to hand over the two Libyans charged with
bombing of the Pan-Am flight over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, in
which 270 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. insist the two Libyans be tried in Britain
or the U.S., a stance rejected by Libya which said they had
already prejudged the two suspects even before trial.
</P>
<P>
The AL supports Libya in terms of reaching a compromise on
expediting a fair trial of the two Libyans in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
The message Swire addressed to Cook included all the proposals
and ideas on settling the dispute along with the British families'
proposal, according to Egypt's Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Swire visited Tripoli in late April, carrying suggestions on
bringing the two Libyan suspects to trial before an international
judiciary body, comprising five judges, presided over by a
Scottish judge to be appointed by the British prime minister,
according to Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The Libya-West showdown has been again put under the spotlight
following the International Court of Justice ruling in February,
saying it has the jurisdiction over the case.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have watered down the ruling and insisted
that the Security council is the body concerned with the issue.
</P>
<P>
A committee which groups representatives of the victims'
families, after a meeting in London in April with Cook, vowed to
pursue pressures on the British government to accept Libya's
compromise solutions to defuse the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
