<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPE Launches Proposal to Reduce CO2 Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) - The International Petroleum Exchange
(IPE) announced Tuesday a proposal to establish a traded market in
Carbon Dioxide (CO2) emissions in order to secure maximum
environmental benefits at minimum economic cost.
</P>
<P>
The proposal which calls for free markets to be allowed to
evolve, has been submitted to John Prescott, UK Deputy Prime
Minister and to the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
The world's first international treaty to combat climate change
was signed in December 1997, and one of the most important
principles to emerge was that of a market based solution to
pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, John Prescott challenged the City of London
to develop a mechanism for trading emissions permits.
</P>
<P>
The IPE said it had positioned itself to take up this
challenge, as a business development team had already undertaken
initial research into the possibilities of emission permit
trading.
</P>
<P>
The IPE is regarded here as a strong supporter of a market
based approach to pollution control as opposed to a top down
regulatory approach such as a tax on emissions.
</P>
<P>
Lynton Jones, Chief Executive of the IPE said: "The UK has a
unique opportunity to lead the rest of the world in the
establishment of a market in CO2 emissions permits."
</P>
<P>
"Market based mechanisms, properly monitored and enforced, are
undoubtedly the most cost effective and flexible way of achieving
pollution reductions," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
