<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Announces Growth in Exports to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- India's exports to Nigeria increased by
38.84 percent in 1997 compared to the previous year, the Indian High
Commission (embassay) to Nigeria said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An embassay statement said that India's exports to the west African
country grew to 201.36 million U.S. dollars last year, from 146.47
million in 1996, the News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the entry of Indian parboiled rice into
the Nigerian market, against stiff competition from Thai rice,
contributed to the increase.
</P>
<P>
Other items which recorded a large increase in India's exports to
Nigeria during the period were transport equipment, machinery and
instruments, agro-chemicals, pharmaceuticals and fine chemicals,
manufactures of metals, and cosmetics and toiletries, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
However, there was some decline in the export of cotton and
man-made yarn, fabrics, paints, enamels and varnishes due to a general
downturn in demand in the Nigerian market, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trade surplus against India slightly declined as the
south Asian country's imports from Nigeria decreased from 1.54 billion
dollars in 1996 to 1.37 billion last year, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
India mainly imports from Nigeria crude oil, cashewnuts, artificial
resins, non-ferrous metals and wood products.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the two countries are finalizing a new
trade agreement followed by the meeting of a joint trade committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
