<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Progress Made, Gaps Remain after Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said here Tuesday that the three-way peace talks in
London made some progress, but some problems remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who had three rounds of the heated talks with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright over the past two days, told
a press conference: "There has been progress, even significant
progress in some of the areas."
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed: "We have not closed all the gaps and we
are working and going to be working in the next few days to see if
we can resolve some of the outstanding issues".
</P>
<P>
"The difficulty arises from a very simple point: we cannot
compromise on Israel's security," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the U.S. proposed peace talks in Washington next week,
Netanyahu noted that a further round of talks in Washington was a
possibility if there was progress in further discussions in London
this week between Israeli officials and U.S. negotiators. 
</P>
