<HEADLINE> Russian Government Presidium Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government's presidium
consisting of eight members was set up on Tuesday, the Interfax
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Newly-appointed Prime Minister, Sergei Kiriyenko, signed a
resolution on the composition of the government's presidium, which
was a new state body introduced as part of the recent government
reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
The eight members of the presidium include the prime minister,
Deputy Prime Ministers Viktor Khristenko, Boris Nemtsov and Oleg
Sysuyev, Science and Technologies Minister Vladimir Bulgak, State
Property Minister Farid Gazizullin, Finance Minister Mikhail
Zadornov and Economics Minister Yakov Urinson.
</P>
<P>
According to a source close to the Cabinet, it is possible in
principle that the presidium's composition will be expanded "up to
nine to 11 members".
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday met with Kiriyenko
to discuss the last appointments, but so far only a land minister
was announced to be appointed.
</P>
<P>
Three deputy prime ministers and 17 ministers has been
appointed by president's decrees after the Russian government was
dismissed by president on March 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
