<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Index of Leading Economic Indicators Rises in March. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A key measure of future economic
activity in the U.S. rose 0.2 percent in March, a sign that
economic growth will continue through the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
The New York-based Conference Board reported today that its
Index of Leading Indicators for March stood at 105.2, up from 105
in February. The gain in March, which matched economists'
projections, marked the leading index's third consecutive monthly
advance.
</P>
<P>
"The leading indicators point to an expanding economy
throughout 1998," the private research group said in the report.
</P>
<P>
Six of the ten indicators that make up the leading index rose
in March. The most significant increases are stock prices and
money supply, each contributing 0.1 percent. The only
significant decrease in March is average factory workweek,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The stock market on Wall Street increased by about 16 percent
so far this year, measured by the Dow Joens industrial average.
More investors believe that a strong economy coupled with low
inflation can continue for some time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
