<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Body Calls for Law on Pesticides </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Federal Environmental
Protection Agency (FEPA) Tuesday called for the enactment of a
law regulating the use of pesticides to safeguard the country's
environment and public health from the effects of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
Such a law was also expected to prevent the dumping of banned
and toxic pesticide formulations from other countries under the
guise of legal trade imports, said FEPA Director-General Raphael
Adewoye, quoted by the official News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
As there are only a few agro-chemical formulating companies in
Nigeria, most of agro-chemical being used in the country are
imported, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the part of FEPA, he said, the organization has put in
place a standing committee to assess various chemicals and
pesticides based on trade benefits derivable for their use, local
research findings, impact on the environment and public health
risks.
</P>
<P>
The committee has begun the registration program for
industrial chemicals, pesticides and ozone depleting substances.
</P>
<P>
According to him, an international convention on the control
and use of pesticides will soon be signed into law this year.
Nigeria is a signatory to the convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
