<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: Egypt's Economic Reform Remarkable Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The economic reform adopted by Egypt
since the early 1990s is a "remarkable success story," according
to a study conducted by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
In presenting the study, the first of its kind conducted by the
IMF on Egypt, Howard Handy, IMF deputy head of Middle East
Department, gave a high mark to Egypt's privatization program at a
news conference here Monday night.
</P>
<P>
He said the Egyptian government succeeded in promoting the
private sector's development and rolling back the "once pervasive
scope of state controls."
</P>
<P>
Egypt has one of the "most rapidly privatizing economies in the
world," ranking among the top four emerging markets in terms of
the pace of privatization, he said.
</P>
<P>
A mission of the IMF is visiting Egypt for talks with senior
officials on the steps taken so far in Egypt's structural
adjustment program.
</P>
<P>
The study said that the Egyptian macroeconomic policy has
"brought much reduced inflation leading to improved public
finances, a stable currency, and a strengthened banking system
together with a sound balance of payments position."
</P>
<P>
From 1991 up till now, Egypt's economic growth has increased
from 2 percent to over 5 percent, inflation decreased from 20
percent to under 4 percent and foreign currency reserves topped 20
billion U.S. dollars. The budget deficit is below one percent of
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
However, the study said that a sustained reinvigoration of
Egypt's structural reform efforts is essential to further
investment and growth in the context of rapid regional economic
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Competition in the global market requires more trade
liberalization, privatization and public sector reform, it
recommended.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Public Sector Minister Atef Obeid said recently that
Egypt will not have a new stand-by agreement with the IMF when the
current one expires in August, saying that Egypt no longer needs
IMF loans as its reform and privatization program is bearing fruit.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 84 public companies have been offered for sale since
1993 and more will be privatized at a rate of 10 companies a
quarter until the government's target of 314 is reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-05 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Peace Efforts Not in Deadlock: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus said on Tuesday that the
efforts to find a solution to the protracted Cyprus problem is in
lack of progress, rather than a complete deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government holds firm position that it is ready to
accept any initiative promoting reunification of Cyprus under a
bizonal and bicommunal formula sponsored by the United Nations,
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides called on the international community to put
pressure on Turkey and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in a
bid to move forward the Cyprus peace process.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the international community will
understand that Denktash and Turkey bear exclusive responsibility
for the lack of progress.
</P>
<P>
Denktash insists that he will not return to peace talks with
Cypriot President and Greek Cypriot leader Glafcos Clerides unless
his entity in northern Cyprus is internationally recognized.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides' comments came one day after United States envoy
for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke wrapped up a three-day visit to
Cyprus, during which he tried in vain to help revive the
intercommunal negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"The government is studying the situation as this has
developed," said the Cypriot spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cypriot National Council will meet on Friday to
discuss the latest developments on the island.
</P>
<P>
"The Council will define the positions of the Cypriot political
leadership on the basis of current developments," he added.
</P>
<P>
The council is the top advisory body to the Cypriot president
for the handling of the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island after a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
