<HEADLINE> UNITA Accused of Preserving Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Defense Minister Pedro
Sebastiao Tuesday accused the National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) of preserving armed forces beyond
the control of the U.N. observer mission.
</P>
<P>
Sebastiao said when massing its forces at the beginning of the
peace process, UNITA sent thousands of women and child soldiers
to the assembly points while hiding up large amounts of its crack
troops.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister made the remarks Tuesday while opening
the third conference of Angola's military attaches.
</P>
<P>
It should be reconsidered whether UNITA is sincere in its
efforts in the peace process and in the implementation of the
1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol, particularly in the re-establishment
of national administration in the areas formerly controlled by it
and in the realization of free movement of personnel and goods
across the country, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The progress in the accomplishment of the above two tasks is
slow because of UNITA's attitude, Sebastiao noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to external military relations, Sebastiao said
Angola's armed intervention in former Zaire and the Republic of
Congo had prompted an early resolution of the conflicts, creating
favorable conditions for realizing peace in Angola as both
countries had provided assistance to UNITA.
</P>
<P>
On the mission of the military attaches, Sebastiao said his
Ministry will arrange courses to train them so that they can know
more about the military and political situation at home and the
policy of national defense in order to defend the interests of
their nation. 
</P>
