<HEADLINE> N. Nigerian State Decries Rampant Blood Hawking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Cases of blood hawking have gone
rampant within the vicinity of government hospitals in northern
Nigeria's Kano State.
</P>
<P>
State Commissioner of Health Adamu Nuhu confirmed that scores
of family men litter around the hospitals ready to exchange a
pint of blood for 1,500 Naira (about 20 U.S. Dollars) in order to
feed their families, the News Agency of Nigeria reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fallout of the present socio-economic circumstance
that compels people to indulge in such practices," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under such situation, Nuhu said his ministry has improved its
blood screening methods to avoid transfusing of blood carrying
HIV virus and other communicable diseases.
</P>
<P>
He also said that efforts are being made to stem the rampant
cases of blood hawking in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
On the scourge of HIV patients in the state, the commissioner
said more than 1,000 cases were recorded in the state in 1997,
which were far above the 1996 record.
</P>
<P>
However, Nuhu said the rise in the number of cases was largely
due to the presence of more screening centers across the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
