<HEADLINE> Albright Briefs Hussein on London Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright made a phone call to King Hussein of Jordan Tuesday,
saying the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks in London have achieved
"some progress."
</P>
<P>
She expressed the intention to "resume the talks in Washington"
in a short time, Jordan's official news agency quoted Albright as
telling the king during the call.
</P>
<P>
Albright has held rounds of separate meetings with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
in London since Monday over the further Israeli withdrawal from
the West Bank and other issues. The talks did not have a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
The planned Washington meeting between the Palestinians and the
Israelis is expected to "lead to initiate the final status
negotiations" between the two sides, she said.
</P>
<P>
For the upcoming talk, the U.S. will insist on its proposal
over the Israeli pullback, Albright added.
</P>
<P>
In the proposal, the U.S. asks Israel to evacuate from 13.1
percent of occupied Palestinian land. Arafat accepted the
proposal but Netanyahu rejected it.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's phone call, Albright also briefed the king on
other aspects of her meetings with the two leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been deadlocked for a
year due to the Jewish settlement expansion in Arab East Jerusalem
and the delayed Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank. 
</P>
