<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Urged to Approve Nuclear Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Sandy Berger, President Bill
Clinton's national security adviser, urged the Senate Tuesday to
ratify a package agreements to ban nuclear testing and limit
weapons and missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
"The future of arms control is now," Berger told the annual
meeting of Business Executives for National Security in
Washington. "We must not let this extraordinary opportunity slip
away."
</P>
<P>
Berger leaves for Moscow on Wednesday to prepare for a meeting
next week between Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin in
Birmingham, Britain, where the Group of Seven countries plus
Russia will hold a summit.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the administration's goal is to see approval
of the pacts by year's end, including the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, an updated Anti-Ballistic Missile (ABM) Defense Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Senate leaders, particularly Foreign Relations Committee
Chairman Jesse Helms have been withholding consideration of the
treaties until after Russian lawmakers ratify START II.
</P>
<P>
In January, Helms wrote Clinton that the test ban treaty,
signed by 149 nations had no chance of entering into force for at
least a decade.
</P>
<P>
"The Senate needs to do what the president asked in his State
of the Union address _ provide its advice and consent for the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty this year," Berger said.
</P>
<P>
Berger added that both the Senate and the Russian parliament of
Duma must also go forward on strategic arms control.
</P>
<P>
The Russia Duma, led by Yeltsin opponents, hasn't approved
START II, partly because some Moscow leaders want assurances the
United States will comply with the antimissile defense treaty,
according to Berger.
</P>
<P>
Since Yeltsin installed a new reform government last month, the
Clinton administration said there's a better chance the stalled
START II will go forward.
</P>
<P>
"In a hopeful sign, we also see more support in the Duma,
reflecting a growing recognition that START II is in Russia's
interest as well as our own," Berger said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
