<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anna Encouraged by ICTR Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U. N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said Tuesday that he was encouraged by the progress made by
the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) in Arusha
while starting a two-day visit to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"In the past six months the new officials of the Tribunal have
effected major improvements in their operations and are moving
ahead to fulfill its objectives," Annan told the U.N. staff in the
Tribunal which is seated inside the Arusha International
Conference Center (AICC) complex in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Annan's remarks were apparently to clear the air over mounting
criticism on the inefficiency of the ICTR in executing cases,
according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal opened its first trial only in January last year,
more than two years after its establishment in November, 1994
under a resolution by the U.N. Security Council. But so far only
two cases are approaching its final stage.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Jean Kambanda, former prime minister of Rwanda,
pleaded guilty to all six charges of genocide while the first
accused, Paul Akayesu, is awaiting for judgement expected to be
delivered before end of next month.
</P>
<P>
"I'm greatly encouraged after holding talks today with the
ICTR President, Mr Laity Kama, and the Registrar, Dr. Agwu
Okali," the U.N. chief told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the U.N. would construct the third
courtroom for the Tribunal at the AICC to speed up hearing of the
cases, urging the staff to continue to show their commitment in
seeking justice.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal staff complain that poor coordination among
judges, registrars and prosecutors, lack of facilities for more
trials to be lodged at the same time, as well as aloofness of
some countries involved are what should be blamed most for the
delay.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 suspects have been indicted by the Tribunal, but
up till now only 23 have been detained in a prison on the
outskirts of Arusha awaiting trial while the other 12 are still
at large with one being set free by the U.S. authorities last
December citing no hard evidence.
</P>
<P>
Among the detainees are 22 Rwandan Hutus including a woman,
and a Belgian journalist who is accused of making broadcasts
inciting violence and hatred against Tutsis in the tiny central
African country.
</P>
<P>
The massacre erupted in April 1994 soon after President
Juvenal Habyarimana, a Hutu, died when his plane was shot down
over capital Kigali. Over 500,000 people, mostly Tutsis and
moderate Hutus, were reportedly killed in the three-month
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, obstacles still remain in the transfer of the
accused from countries concerned while most witnesses could not
be able to offer useful evidence at the courts, the U.N.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived from Nairobi, Kenya, toured the ICTR
premises and attended a court session before departing for a
sightseeing of the well-known Ngorongoro Crater National Park and
the descend Crater accompanied by his wife Nane Annan.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief is expected to arrive in Dar es Salaam on
Wednesday to meet with Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa and
other senior officials as well as the U.N. staff before he leaves
for Rwanda and Burundi. Tanzania is the fifth leg of his
eight-country African tour. He had visited Ethiopia, Eritrea,
D'jibouti and Kenya before coming to Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
