<HEADLINE> Hamas Ready to Contain Disputes With PNA: Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting leader of the Palestinian
radical movement Hamas Sheikh Ahmed Yassin expressed readiness on
Tuesday to contain disputes with the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
"We are one people, our objective is one and the same, our
enemy is one, and we can not possibly engage in hostilities with
our brothers unless we have lost our senses, and (we) are ready to
contain any differences," Yassin told a news conference held here.
</P>
<P>
He said the ties between Hamas, or Islamic Resistance Movement,
and the PNA are based on fraternity and love.
</P>
<P>
Yassin termed the London talks as "waste of time" and "another
crafty deception" of the Jews and the west.
</P>
<P>
On Monday and Tuesday, United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright held separate talks with PNA President Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in London in
a bid to bridge the gap between the two sides over Israeli troop
pullback from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But Albright failed to persuade Netanyahu to accept a U.S.
proposal calling for Israeli withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank. The PNA has agreed to accept the proposal in principle.
</P>
<P>
Yassin called on Arafat to reconsider and avert the path he has
been pursuing and agree to Hamas movement in the best interests of
the Palestinian cause and the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
On the murder of Mohi Sherif, Yassin voiced absolute confidence
that Israelis killed the Hamas chief bombmaker, whether directly
or indirectly, and would have to bear the consequences.
</P>
<P>
Hamas will not give up its right or forsake the revenge, he
said, adding that it will respond at appropriate time.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Hamas cooperation with Islamic organizations in the
Islamic world, Yassin said Hamas will cooperate with whoever helps
it in its cause.
</P>
<P>
He said his visits to the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and other
Arab states are aimed at contacting with the leaders of the
countries, briefing them on the latest developments of the
Palestinian problem and exchanging views.
</P>
<P>
The tour is primarily part of the efforts to serve the
Palestinian cause and promote PNA's interests rather than breach
them.
</P>
<P>
Yassin arrived here on Monday after wrapping up a visit to
Iran, before which he has traveled to Egypt, Saudi Arabia and
Qatar. 
</P>
