<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs from
Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Manufactures Association Vice President
Doron Tamir said early this week that 1998 would be "a lost year"
for Israel from the economic perspective.
</P>
<P>
Tamir said that "1999 may also be lost unless there is a
change in the government's economic policy and unless economic
leaders stop talking and start doing."
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli government is making efforsts to join
the European Union (EU)'s fifth research and development program,
which will start in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the four-year program to Israel, an associate
member of the EU, is some 150 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Elbit Systems company has won a contract
from the American Lockheed Martin company to install its
pilot-helmet display system into future F-22 jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
The contract is for some 4,000 helmet systems and is estimated
to be worth hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian-Israeli Committee for the Qualified
Industrial Zone (QIZ) in Jordan's northern city Irbid Monday
reached consensus on the administrative and technical procedures
necessary for running the QIZ.
</P>
<P>
The procedures will soon be applied to speed up the opening of
the QIZ, said Sameer Omaish, head of the Jordanian side of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
Products manufactured at the QIZ, if involving an Israeli input
of at least 11.7 percent, can be exported to the United States
duty free under the agreement signed by Jordan and the U.S.
last November. 
</P>
