<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Seeks COMESA Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Egypt, a north African country, is
possibly to be admitted into the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA) next month, a local source told Xinhua
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian government delegation is in Lusaka to discuss
Cairo's application for the membership of COMESA with Erastus
Mwencha, acting secretary general of COMESA with its headquarters
based in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
A COMESA summit to be held in Kinshasa next month is expected
to admit Egypt into the 20-member grouping, said the source.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here Tuesday, COMESA secretariat said
Egypt's participation will strengthen regional integration in a
larger area.
</P>
<P>
The report said Egypt will provide strength to the region not
only through its productivity but also through its consumptive
capacity.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 63 million, Egypt will provide a big
market for some of the exports of the current COMESA member
states, it said.
</P>
<P>
The total trade of COMESA member countries was estimated to be
30 billion U.S. Dollars in 1994 while Egypt's total trade in the
same year was estimated to be 15 billion Dollars, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Once admitted into COMESA, the north African country is likely
to benefit from the huge hydro-electric power potential of the
Democratic Republic of Congo, also a COMESA member, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Plans are underway to supply Egypt with electricity from
Congo's Equatoria Province through another COMESA member, Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Congo's hydro-power potential is so vast that from Egypt the
power could be further extended to the Middle East countries and
Turkey, according to a COMESA official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Appeals for Donor Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
appealed to foreign donors Tuesday to continue supporting his
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba stressed that any future success of his country
depends on western aid. He also reiterated that his government's
far-reaching economic reforms are irreversible.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made ahead of Zambia's aid consultative
meeting with the Paris club members billed for next week in
Paris. Zambia's 35 percent of its 1998 financial budget is
supposed to rely on western aid, according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
However, the western donors froze their aid to Zambia
following the country's foiled military coup last October and
subsequent detentions of oppositions leaders including former
President Kenneth Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
They also set a precondition for aid support that the aid will
not be released until Zambia's state-owned copper mines, which
usually covered more than 90 percent of the country's total
foreign exchange earnings, are privatized.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has achieved macro-economic stability after years of
neglect and mismanagement, Chiluba said, warning that the donors'
failure to provide further aid to his country will jeopardize
such gains.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Zambia's gross domestic product registered 3.5
percent growth and its inflation rate fell down to 18.6 percent
from 35 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
As for the country's privatization progress, Chiluba, who
carried out a western-style free market economy instead of
Kaunda's command economy after coming to power in 1991, said his
country's selling off of state-run enterprises is progressing as
planned with more than 130 firms sold or liquidated.
</P>
<P>
"We have implemented every rule in the game of economics,"
said Chiluba, adding, "We have done what most countries have so
far failed to achieve and surely our efforts deserve support and
not repudiation."
</P>
<P>
Western donors will meet in Paris on May 12 and 13 to review
Zambia's economic performance and assess its request for further
aid of about 165 million U.S. Dollars in project support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Encouraged by ICTR Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U. N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said Tuesday that he was encouraged by the progress made by
the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) in Arusha
while starting a two-day visit to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"In the past six months the new officials of the Tribunal have
effected major improvements in their operations and are moving
ahead to fulfill its objectives," Annan told the U.N. staff in the
Tribunal which is seated inside the Arusha International
Conference Center (AICC) complex in northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Annan's remarks were apparently to clear the air over mounting
criticism on the inefficiency of the ICTR in executing cases,
according to a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal opened its first trial only in January last year,
more than two years after its establishment in November, 1994
under a resolution by the U.N. Security Council. But so far only
two cases are approaching its final stage.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Jean Kambanda, former prime minister of Rwanda,
pleaded guilty to all six charges of genocide while the first
accused, Paul Akayesu, is awaiting for judgement expected to be
delivered before end of next month.
</P>
<P>
"I'm greatly encouraged after holding talks today with the
ICTR President, Mr Laity Kama, and the Registrar, Dr. Agwu
Okali," the U.N. chief told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the U.N. would construct the third
courtroom for the Tribunal at the AICC to speed up hearing of the
cases, urging the staff to continue to show their commitment in
seeking justice.
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal staff complain that poor coordination among
judges, registrars and prosecutors, lack of facilities for more
trials to be lodged at the same time, as well as aloofness of
some countries involved are what should be blamed most for the
delay.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 suspects have been indicted by the Tribunal, but
up till now only 23 have been detained in a prison on the
outskirts of Arusha awaiting trial while the other 12 are still
at large with one being set free by the U.S. authorities last
December citing no hard evidence.
</P>
<P>
Among the detainees are 22 Rwandan Hutus including a woman,
and a Belgian journalist who is accused of making broadcasts
inciting violence and hatred against Tutsis in the tiny central
African country.
</P>
<P>
The massacre erupted in April 1994 soon after President
Juvenal Habyarimana, a Hutu, died when his plane was shot down
over capital Kigali. Over 500,000 people, mostly Tutsis and
moderate Hutus, were reportedly killed in the three-month
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, obstacles still remain in the transfer of the
accused from countries concerned while most witnesses could not
be able to offer useful evidence at the courts, the U.N.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived from Nairobi, Kenya, toured the ICTR
premises and attended a court session before departing for a
sightseeing of the well-known Ngorongoro Crater National Park and
the descend Crater accompanied by his wife Nane Annan.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief is expected to arrive in Dar es Salaam on
Wednesday to meet with Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa and
other senior officials as well as the U.N. staff before he leaves
for Rwanda and Burundi. Tanzania is the fifth leg of his
eight-country African tour. He had visited Ethiopia, Eritrea,
D'jibouti and Kenya before coming to Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
