<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Peace Talks End with No Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The two-day Middle East peace talks
ended in London Tuesday afternoon with some progress but no
breakthrough in revitalizing the deadlocked Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright held several rounds of talks with both Israeli Prime
Minister Benjami Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
in an effort to bridge the "significant gaps" between the Israelis
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Although the London talks, started early Monday, were forced
into second day of heated argument, the Americans failed to create
dramatic miracle in bringing Netanyahu and Arafat to the same
table due to differences over a crucial new American peace
initiative under which Israel will have to cede another 13 percent
of West Bank.
</P>
<P>
With no breakthrough in near sight, U.S. President Bill Clinton
invited Israeli and Palestinian leaders to Washington next Monday
for another rounds of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who has accepted the U.S. invitation for another
meeting, said, "It is true that we still face obstacles from the
Israeli side. I hope as soon as possible to see this progress in
reality."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, whose government is under immense pressure to accept
the new U.S. proposal, painted a positive picture of the London
talks by saying: "there has been progress, even significant
progress in some areas."
</P>
<P>
But he also admitted: "We have not closed all the gaps and we
are working and going to be working in the next few days to see if
we can resolve some of the outstanding issues."
</P>
<P>
On the Clinton proposed Washington meeting, Netanyahu noted
that a further round of talks was a possibility if there was
progress in further discussions in London between Israeli and
American negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who chaired the two-day London talks, urged both
sides, especially the Israelis, to make efforts in bringing the
Middle East peace talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
"We have a strategic opportunity to put the (Middle East) peace
process back on track and we can not afford to lose it," she said,
adding, "If the issues are resolved, President Clinton is prepared
to invite the parties to launch accelerated final status
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process was plunged into a stalemate for
more than a year due to Israel's staunchly maintained Jewish
settlement construction projects in defiance of the opposition by
the Palestinians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
