<HEADLINE> 3 Unionist Parties Unite Against N.Irish Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Politicians from three pro-British
parties in Northern Ireland joined forces Tuesday to oppose the
historic peace agreement reached last month.
</P>
<P>
"We now realize they can give no guarantee that if you vote
`yes' in this referendum, you will have peace," William Thompson,
a member of the largest Ulster Unionist Party, told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the pro-Irish guerrilla groups were continuing their
sectarian shootings, attempted bombings and explosions even after
the peace deal was struck on April 10.
</P>
<P>
"We see the number of people who have been murdered, we see the
bombs which have gone off, and it's clear that this document will
not bring peace," Reuters quoted Thompson as saying in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Half of the party's 10 parliament members have expressed
opposition to the deal, though the party has managed to gain 72
percent support for the accord.
</P>
<P>
Other opponents include the small Democratic Unionist Party led
by Ian Paisley and the U.K. Unionist Party led by Robert
McCartney.
</P>
<P>
They fear the deal's provisions for new institutions uniting
Northern Ireland with the republic south of the Irish border mark
the beginning of the end of Northern Ireland's union with Britain.
</P>
<P>
The province's 60 percent Protestant majority is split over the
deal, though opinion polls show majority support for the deal on
both sides of the island, where concurrent referendum votes will
be held on May 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
