<HEADLINE> European Shares Down on Interest Rate Rise Concern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
suspended Monday's rally and ended lower Tuesday, dragged down by
a weaker Wall Street, fresh concern over interest rate hike and
the European Union summit compromise on the leadership of the
European Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index on the London market, which did not
open Monday for a bank holiday, fell below the 6,000-point level
to end at 5,986.5, down 23.8 points or 0.40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that leading shares were dragged into the red amid
concerns about euro interest rate prospects.
</P>
<P>
Profit-taking across the continent was sparked by an unexpected
0.5 percent rate rise in Denmark and fears that Germany would
follow suit. Meanwhile, opening weakness on Wall Street helped
compound the market's dull tone.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed 82.63 points or 1.55 percent
down on the DAX-30 index after a very weak dollar prompted further
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
One analyst said that the market were surprised by the weakness
of the dollar, which made many investors cautious.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, French shares retreated as investors took
profits amid growing concerns about European interest rates, with
the CAC-40 index closing down 29.34 points or 0.74 percent at
3,944.91. 
</P>
