<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Organizers of the inaugural Asian
Bowling Tour (ABT) have decided to call off the China Masters Cup
due to timing and logistical difficulties, it was announced here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The China Masters Cup, set for May 2-3, is the second of the
five Masters Cup events of this year's Tour, with the first one
being the Malaysian Masters Cup in March.
</P>
<P>
Tour organizers had postponed the event due to timing problems
but had finally had to cancel it as they had failed to put things
together for a high caliber event.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, logistical difficulties lead to delays which we
felt imposed time constraints not conducive to planning a
world-class event," said Richard Young, vice-president of
Operations for the Tour.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward however to the China Masters Cup debuting in
the future seasons of the ABT," he added.
</P>
<P>
The next Masters Cup event would be the Philippine Master Cup
set for June 13-14.
</P>
<P>
"Though it is a pity that the China leg was canceled, it is
anticipated that the Philippines Masters Cup will see top caliber
bowlers from all parts of Asia gathering together again to match
their skill against one another to acquire points for qualifying
into the Grand Slam Finals," said Vivien Fung, president of the
FIQ-WTBA Asian Zone.
</P>
<P>
Following the Philippines Masters Cup will be the Hong Kong
Masters Cup on July 13-14 and the Singapore Masters Cup on August
17-18.
</P>
<P>
The Grand Slam Finals is scheduled for January next year in
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Each participant will accumulate their tour ranking points and
the top 16 ranked men and women bowlers from their tour rankings
will qualify for the Grand Slam Finals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
