<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Pick Up Modestly in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. factory orders picked up
modestly in March, but the first quarter of this year was
relatively soft due to Asian financial and economic crisis, the
Commerce Department reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Factory orders which represents the future production,
increased 0.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted 336.2 billion U.S.
dollars following a 0.7 percent drop in February, according to the
report. Orders for the quarter as a whole are down 0.8 percent
from the fourth quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
U.S. manufacturers, the export-reliant aircraft industry in
particular, have been hurt by soft demand in Asian countries.
However, the weakness hasn't yet stimulated unemployment or
dampened American consumers' confidence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, shipments of factory goods, a measure of current
production, jumped 0.8 percent to a seasonally adjusted 340.5
billion dollars in March, the third increase in four months.
Shipments for the quarter were up 0.8 percent over the fourth
quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
The faster pace of shipments, compared with new orders, helped
manufacturers to lower the backlog of unfilled orders for the
third time in four months. It dipped 0.8 percent in March to a
seasonally adjusted 538.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In March, factory orders were led by a 4.1 percent increase for
computers and other office equipment. Overall, durable goods,
expensive items expected to last at least three years, rose 0.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Those included a 3 percent rise for stone, clay and glass
products, a 1.1 percent rise for communications equipment, a 4.4
percent gain for medical instruments and a 7.9 percent increase
for electronic components.
</P>
<P>
However, orders for aircraft slumped 16.6 percent, on top of a
34.8 percent plunge in February. Orders fell 4.2 percent for
primary metals such as steel, 0.1 percent for fabricated metal
products. They also declined for electric lighting and wiring and
engines and turbines.
</P>
<P>
Non-durable goods orders were unchanged from the month before.
Orders declined for chemicals, but increased for printed
materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
