<HEADLINE> Westerners Should Know More about Chinese Culture: Sinologists (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
She said that she thought that Westerners have not got enough
knowledge about Chinese culture, though more and more Westerners
are learning the Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
"Before the 1970s there were few students at Harvard University
learning the Chinese language. But now the number of students
learning Chinese ranks third on the campus, after those learning
French or Spanish," said Professor Steven Owen from Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
Owen attributed the change to the fact that China is becoming
stronger and no longer so unfamiliar to and far away from the
Western world, and that Westerners are changing their attitude
toward culture.
</P>
<P>
Almost the same reasons led Roland Felber, professor of Chinese
history at Berlin's Humboldt University, to the conclusion that it
is time for East and West to hold dialogue on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Felber, an overseas student in the department of history at
Beijing University in the 1950s, spoke highly of Cai Yuanpei,
president of the university some 80 years ago, calling him a
pioneer in modern Chinese history to attempt equal exchanges of
Eastern and Western cultures.
</P>
<P>
"He did not advocate 'total Westernization', but preferred
Chinese culture with modern characteristics; he promoted spreading
Chinese culture to the West, but without arrogance," Felber said.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing in cultural exchange is to find out
what will benefit humanity, no matter whether it is Chinese or
Western," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Cultural exchanges are bilateral," said Allen. "In this regard
my paper could also be titled: 'Why Chinese should learn from
Western Culture'." 
</P>
