<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Hi-Tech Zone Celebrates Tenth Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China's first ``Silicon Valley''
celebrated its tenth anniversary here today.
</P>
<P>
The Zhongguancun hi-tech zone, officially known as the Haidian
Experimental Zone of Hi-Tech Development, has become a pillar of
Beijing's industry since it was set up on May 8, 1988.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten years enterprises in the zone have racked up a
total turnover of 119.5 billion yuan (about 14.4 billion US
dollars), contributing nearly 50 percent of the annual growth of
the local industry.
</P>
<P>
Now the zone has 4,525 hi-tech enterprises, including the
country's largest computer manufacturers such as Legend and Stone.
</P>
<P>
The pillar industries of the experimental zone are
electronic information, digital technology, new materials and
energy, medicine and bio-technology.
</P>
<P>
The zone has attracted 790 million US dollars of foreign
investment so far.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it has transferred more than 2,500 items of
technology to other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The zone will hold a computer festival May 8-12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
