<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Firm to Scrap Water Export Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A small Canadian company that planned
to export lake water to Asia is now preparing to abandon the idea.
</P>
<P>
The company said its proposal to ship Lake Superior water
abroad was not intended to create an international incident, but
to countries that need fresh water.
</P>
<P>
"If the Canadian government decides to revoke the permit, then
the Nova Group will abide by that decision," said president John
Febbraro.
</P>
<P>
Nova Group, based in the Ontario city of Sault Ste. Mario on
the eastern tip of the lake, was last week granted the first-ever
permit from the Ontario provincial government to export water from
Lake Superior to Asia.
</P>
<P>
The company hoped to take up to 600 million liters of water a
year for the next five years from the lake for shipping abroad.
</P>
<P>
However, the planned sale of lake water had raised fears that
Canada could lose control of its fresh water supply to water
markets.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy voiced his
strong objection to the proposed water export, and is scheduled to
meet Ontario Environment Minister Norm Sterling on Wednesday to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
The federal government was "examining various pieces of
legislation" to determine if there was a way of preventing the
export, Axworthy said early this week.
</P>
<P>
"What we are looking at is the real question of the large-scale
export of fresh water, which we certainly have always taken a
strong stand against," Axworthy said. "It is a matter of some
real concern."
</P>
<P>
While admitting the planned export amount was "reasonably small"
compared to the normal flow of water out of the lake, the minister
said that the action could set a precedent and encourage companies
from Canada and the United States to draw on limited fresh water
resources for profit.
</P>
<P>
The Ontario Environment Ministry said it granted the export
permit on the grounds that the company had demonstrated the project
would result in no significant environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. government official was reported as saying that
Washington was concerned the exports could violate a 1909 treaty
which established joint Canada-U.S. management of the Great
Lakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
