<HEADLINE> Russia, Uzbekistan Agree on Cooperation Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his Uzbek counterpart Islam Karimov decided to sign a 10-year
cooperation treaty when they met at the Kremlin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will be signed during Yeltsin's official visit to
Tashkent, capital of Uzbekistan, in early October, reported the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Karimov also agreed to raise the level of the
Russia-Uzbekistan joint commission and appoint Russian Prime
Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and his Uzbek counterpart Utkir Sultanov
as its co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement was issued following the talks. The two
presidents also signed agreements on the status of correspondents
in both countries and on establishing information and culture
centers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a cooperation agreement was reached on the design,
mass assembly and supplies of Il-76MF and Il-76 TF aircraft and
their modifications.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Karimov also exchanged views on the situation in
Afghanistan, which they described as "explosive".
</P>
<P>
They noted a further escalation of tension in Afghanistan would
pose a serious threat to its national interests and the security
of countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Karimov arrived in Moscow Tuesday for a three-day state visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
