<HEADLINE> British TV Company Probes Fake Drugs Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A major British television company
Carlton said on Wednesday it was investigating claims that a
ward-winning documentary on Colombian drugs cartel were faked.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Guardian newspaper said on Wednesday that a 1996
documentary made by independent Carlton Communications Plc on the
Cali cartel and its heroin smuggling route between South America
and London, contained a number of major deceptions.
</P>
<P>
Carlton spokesman Peter Rushton told reporters the company was
investigating many of the issues revealed in the newspaper in a
full scale.
</P>
<P>
The hour-long program, The Connection, featured an exclusive
interview with a man who claimed to be the number three of the
Cali cartel and also showed a drugs courier, known as a "mule",
swallowing packets of heroin before boarding a flight to London.
</P>
<P>
But the Guardian alleged that the interviewee was a retired
bank cashier with low-level connections to the drug world.
</P>
<P>
Carlton sold the program to 14 countries, winning eight
international awards and world-wide praise for its educational
content.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Independent Television Commission (ITC), Britain's
television watchdog, was aware of the reports, saying it was
"waiting to see Carlton's reaction to these reports."
</P>
<P>
The ITC has the power to withdraw Carlton's broadcasting
license if it has enough evidence and reason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
