<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Westerners Should Know More about Chinese Culture, Sinologists (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- "I believed that what we Westerners
do and think was natural before I touched Chinese culture, but
later I changed my ideas," said Professor Sarah Allan, a
52-year-old US sinologist.
</P>
<P>
"Because I knew then that in the Far East there has been a
totally different way of thinking and living since ancient times,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps that is why this professor of Chinese history at
Dartmouth College offered a paper to the International Symposium
on Sinology which opened here today, discussing why Westerners
should get to know more about Chinese Culture.
</P>
<P>
"Now the Westerners are doubting their traditional culture, and
a way to solve the problem might be to learn from another
culture," she said. "By learning from another culture, we may
check and improve our own thinking."
</P>
<P>
Allan is among some 300 Sinologists from 17 countries and
regions who will continue to discuss Chinese language and
literature, history, philosophy and archaeology, in the next two
days at the Fragrant Hills Hotel.
</P>
<P>
Like many other foreign sinologists at the symposium, Allen
regards Chinese culture as an important part of world
civilization. "We will be more aware of the nature of mankind once
we know this country, which is most distant to us in terms of
culture," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I am touched by the beauty of ancient Chinese jades or
bronzes. And when I read a poem from the 'Book of Odes' or a
passage from the 'Zhuang Zi', I am also enthralled. Then I realize
that no matter how distant we are in time, space and cultural
atmosphere, we share a common humanity," she wrote in the paper
she presented at the symposium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
