<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Call for Cooperation in Biotechnology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at an international
seminar here today called for international cooperation in
biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
"To increase international cooperation, especially the
cooperation between developing and developed countries, and to
narrow the gap of biotechnology between them, will be of great
significance for the world's stability and development," said
Professor Zhou Zenquan of Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said that developing countries should not count on
applying biotechnology to solve their food problems for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
Although there is worldwide optismism on biotechnology's
prospects for the 21st century, Professor Ray Wu of Cornell
University said that developing countries will have obstacles to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
He said that biotechnology will play a big role in agriculture,
but that it will be more useful for developed countries.
</P>
<P>
"For developing countries, the issue relates not only to
technology but also to the way of funding input and research," the
U.S. biology professor said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting revealed that because of the shortage of research
funds, many developing countries have to import seeds from Western
biotechnology companies. Experts say that this trend has made
developed countries the biggest beneficiary in the biotech
revolution.
</P>
<P>
People suffering from food shortages mainly live in developing
countries and account for the biggest proportion of the world's
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
