<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1630 GMT, May 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Germany's Daimler-Benz AG confirmed Wednesday that it
has entered into talks with U.S. carmaker Chrysler on a possible
mega-merger.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday morning, Daimler-Benz said the
merger could take the form of a share swap, with the two forming a
joint company.
</P>
<P>
However, Daimler also stressed that there was no certainty that
an agreement could be reached. (Germany-Chrysler-Merger)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Palestinian permanent delegate to the Arab League
said Wednesday that a "weak" U.S. stance has led to the failure of
the London meetings and overcast the peace talks in Washington
next week.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the middle East News Agency, Mohamed Sobeih
expressed pessimism over another round of back-to-back talks
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to have with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Washington next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"My pessimism is attributed to the hostile and antagonistic
stance by Israeli Premier Netanyahu vis-a-vis the Oslo Agreement,"
he said. (Egypt-Arafat Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Crimes against foreigners by right-wing extremists in
Germany last year hit a record high in the post-war era, a German
government report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of crimes by far-right groups amounted to 11,719
last year, up 34 percent from 1996, breaking the previous record
of 10,561 cases registered in 1993, German Interior Minister
Manfred Kanther said in the report.
</P>
<P>
The total number of right-wing extremists in Germany was
estimated at about 48,400 by the end of last year, up seven
percent from a year ago. About 7,600 of these people were
classified as militants, up 19 percent when compared with 1996.
(Germany-Crimes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek urged the
Palestinians and Israelis to come up with "frank" decisions at the
upcoming Washington peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian minister made the appeal following his talks with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Wednesday on developments of
the Middle East peace process in light of the London meeting.
</P>
<P>
The back-to-back talks Palestinian and Israeli leaders had with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright have failed to produce
any real progress on the ground except promises of more talks in
Washington on Monday. (Egypt-Norway-Peace Process) 
</P>
