<HEADLINE> HK to Step Up Enforcement Against Speeding At Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Marine Police will step
up enforcement actions against speeding and unlicensed operations
of pleasure vessels in Hong Kong waters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here Wednesday, Poon Tze-chung,
divisional commander of the Marine Police, said the actions aim at
improving water safety and deterring unqualified persons from
operation on pleasure vessels.
</P>
<P>
"We are also considering actions against owners of pleasure
craft who permit their vessels to be operated by unqualified
persons," Poon said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that despite continuous efforts to remind masters and
operators of marine crafts to engage in a safe speed, speeding
remains a major problem.
</P>
<P>
To tackle the problem more effectively, the Marine Police have
procured five laser guns, each cost 40,000 HK dollars (5,128 U.S.
dollars) this April.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the new laser guns will make the job of
mounting anti-speeding operations less manpower intensive and
eventually more such offense will be detected, he said.
</P>
<P>
Poon also noted that greater emphasis will be placed on
enforcing speed-restricted zones this year, particularly on
weekends and public holidays.
</P>
<P>
Besides actions against speeding and unlicensed operations of
pleasure vessels, the Marine Police also assist the Marine
Department in conducting routine checks on safety equipment of
pleasure vessels, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
