<HEADLINE> Workshop on Innovation, Technology Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's Commission
on Innovation and Technology organized on Wednesday a workshop to
promote awareness of issues related to innovation and technology.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 people from the local academic and business
community attended the half-day workshop.
</P>
<P>
The first session of the workshop, which was chaired by the
commission's chairman Professor Chang-Lin Tien, focused on
academia-industry collaboration.
</P>
<P>
Panelist Prof. S. Simon Wong from the Electrical Engineering
Department, Stanford University, emphasized smooth collaborations
between university, industry and government, which "are essential
to the establishment and growth of a high technology industry."
</P>
<P>
The second session centered on collaboration between Hong Kong
and its economic hinterland -- China's inland areas, with
President of the Chinese Academy of Sciences Prof. Lu Yongxiang
and Executive Director of Hong Kong Productivity Council Thomas
Tang Koon-yiu among the four panelists.
</P>
<P>
They highlighted the complementarity of Hong Kong and China's
inland areas, saying that collaboration in developing technology
will benefit both.
</P>
<P>
There are many opportunities for collaboration, especially in
such areas as information technology, product design, financial
services, energy and environment, said the panelists.
</P>
<P>
The commission was appointed by Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region Tung Chee Hwa in March to
advise him on the measures necessary to drive forward innovation
and technology development in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It will submit an interim report to Tung by October this year,
and will complete all its tasks within 12 to 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
