<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows Not to Bow to U.S. Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu reiterated Wednesday that he would not bow to U.S.
pressure over the issue of next redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Netanyahu said that he
might reject the invitation by U.S. President Bill Clinton
for peace talks in Washington next week if attending the meeting
meant yielding to the American dictates.
</P>
<P>
He noted that "he is ready to go, but Israel is a sovereign
country and will not accept certain condition."
</P>
<P>
After the two-day separate talks in London with Netanyahu and
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright announced Tuesday that
if Israel accepted the U.S. proposals, Clinton would invite the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders to Washington next Monday for
accelerated final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
The American peace plan calls on Israel to hand over 13.1
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians during the second
redeployment in return for the fulfillment of the Palestinian
commitments for combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu convened the inner cabinet meeting Wednesday to
discuss the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Netanyahu briefed Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon, Defense Minister yitzhak Mordechai, and Trade and
Industry Minister Natan Sharansky on his talks in London.
</P>
<P>
No reports on the outcome of the meeting were available. But
Sharon has told reporters that Israel must not hand over more than
9 percent of the West Bank in the further redeployment and every
extra percent handback will harm Israeli national security.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA Culture and Information Minister Yasser Abed
Rabbo said Wednesday that the London talks were completely a
failure, and the Palestinians were not hopeful that there would be
different results in Washington next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
