<HEADLINE> Six Killed in Philippine Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- All six people aboard a single-engine
Cessna plane perished Wednesday as the aircraft plunged into a
remote village in a central Philippine province, the Philippine
News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The plane, a Cessna 206, crashed Wednesday morning on a
domestic flight from General Santos City in South Cotabato
province to Manila with a scheduled stop for refueling at Mactan
airport in Cebu city.
</P>
<P>
The plane's wreckage was found in an open field in Tubigan town
in Bohol province, said Frederick San Felix, manager of the
General Santos City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
San Felix said the plane took off at around 8:32 a.m. local
time with its two pilots and four passengers.
</P>
<P>
The plane's pilot made its last radio contact with the Mactan
air control tower at around 11:00 a.m., informing the tower that
it was about 15 miles from the airport.
</P>
<P>
The plane was earlier declared missing by the Air
Transportation Office (ATO) in Manila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
