<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Computer Company Produces One Million PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Intel Chairman and CEO Andrew Grove
received the one-millionth PC that China's Legend Group produced,
at a celebration ceremony here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"I never thought that Legend would have such a wonderful
celebration today when I visited the company in 1994," Grove told
the several hundred representatives of Chinese and international
telecommunications industry, journalists and government officials
at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Today's Legend is very, very different from the Legend of four
years ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past eight years Legend has boosted its annual
production and sales of PCs to over 500,000 from 2,000 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
It occupied 10.7 percent of China's PC market in 1997, and it
is expected to increase its market share to over 20 percent and
annual sales to 1.5 million PCs by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yuanqing, general manager of the computer company under
the Legend Group, said that Legend can do what foreign computer
companies cannot do in the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
He said that Legend has a good understanding of the needs of
Chinese users, and focuses on applications and functions of the
PCs.
</P>
<P>
He noted that, at present, the solutions that foreign
companies designed for China's small- and medium-sized enterprises
are actually missing the target.
</P>
<P>
"Such solutions can only be used in certain departments of
large companies in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Legend Chairman and CEO Liu Chuanzhi said that the key to
Legend's success in competing with overseas manufacturers is
"cutting costs."
</P>
<P>
He said that the operation cost of Legend is about one-third of
that of its foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
"China's reform and opening-up drive has created an environment
of fair competition for Legend and other PC manufacturers," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Legend will concentrate its resources on
consolidating and expanding its position in the domestic
market. It will strive to become one of the top ten PC
manufacturers in the world, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 Chinese manufacturers took more than 60 percent of
China's PC market, which is the sixth-largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that Legend will further strengthen cooperation with
foreign manufacturers. Now it buys Intel chips and test-runs
Intel's newly developed chips on its products.
</P>
<P>
Grove said that he will place the one-millionth Legend PC in a
museum that Intel has set up in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
