<HEADLINE> Drilling of First Sino-Foreign Oil Well Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Drilling of the first oil well by
Chinese and foreign companies at the Shengli Oilfield, in east
China's Shandong Province, started today.
</P>
<P>
This is a joint venture between the Shengli Oilfield, the
second-largest in China, and the Energy Development
Co. (EDC) of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield produces 1.5 million tons of offshore oil
annually. To increase ther output, the oilfield joined hands with
EDC to develop a 249-sq-km area in the shallow waters of Bohai
Bay, which has a verified reserve of 54.4 million tons of oil.
</P>
<P>
According to a contract signed between the two partners, they
are expected to drill three wells this year. 
