<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Fights Against Fraud Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union is stepping up
fight against the rising number of cases of fraud and financial
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
A 1998-1999 work program was adopted Wednesday by the European
Commission, the EU executive body, to deal with the problem after
an annual report revealed Wednesday that fraud cases increased
from 4,552 in 1996 to 5,162 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The cost entailed by fraud rose from 1.3 billion European
Currency Units (1.17 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996 to 1.4 billion
ECUs (1.25 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very worrying phenomenon, especially since we know
that these syndicates also are involved in drug smuggling, trade
in weapons, corruption of public officials and money laundering."
said European Commissioner Anita Gradin.
</P>
<P>
"And now we can see them operating from neighboring countries
in the east, undermining their progress toward the rule of law,"
said Gradin, the commissioner in charge of financial control and
fight against fraud.
</P>
<P>
When asked to elaborate, the commissioner said that some former
border security officials in central and eastern European
countries had formed gangs of their own to smuggle weapons as well
as cigarettes, alcohol, sugar and butter.
</P>
<P>
There are 10 probes underway in the commission itself for cases
involving discipline, efficiency and corruption, she said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner called for her institution to ratify the work
program into legislation so as to give the fight an effective
instrument.
</P>
<P>
She said that she would present the work program to the next
European Council meeting of economy and finance ministers this
month to help quicken the ratification process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
