<HEADLINE> S. Korea Exports to Rise by 7.6 Percent in 1998: Think-tank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's exports are expected to
rise by 7.6 percent to 146.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 despite
the worsening business environment at home and abroad, the Samsung
Economic Research Institute said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But South Korean exporters will meet much tougher trade
competition in the international market in the coming months, the
institute said.
</P>
<P>
Exports by the steel, shipbuilding and petrochemical sectors
will likely show relatively high annual growth rates ranging from
16 percent to 18 percent while textiles, electronics and machinery
are likely to register near-zero or negative growth, the institute
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports will noticeably drop in the second half of
this year, reducing the total import volume by 11.3 percent to 128.5
billion U.S. dollars from last year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, this year's trade surplus will be around 20
billion U.S. dollars, added the Samsung institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
