<HEADLINE> Chinese, Chilean Foreign Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Tang
Jiaxuan and his Chilean counterpart Jose Miguel Insulza, in talks
here this afternoon, agreed that Sino-Chilean relations have
witnessed satisfying development since the two countries forged
diplomatic ties 28 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Tang said, in the 1990s the two countries have enjoyed fruitful
cooperation in many areas, shared close or identical views on
major global issues, and supported each other and coordinated
closely in world affairs. Bilateral trade has also grown rapidly,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Chile has become one of China's most important trade partners
in Latin America, and the trade volume between the two countries
account for 10 percent of trade between China and Latin America as
a whole, although Chile only has four percent of the population of
the region.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that China values its friendly cooperation with
Chile, and considers the country as an important cooperative
partner in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Based on the principles of mutual trust, equality, mutual
benefit and complementarity, China is ready to make joint efforts
with Chile to forge long-term stable relations of beneficial
cooperation geared to the 21st century, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Insulza agreed with Tang's view on furthering economic and
trade relations between the two nations, and said that he looked
forward to closer bilateral relations of cooperation in various
areas.
</P>
<P>
Insulza said his country will continue to stick to its "one China"
stand.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi
and Chilean Ambassador to China Octavio Errazuriz Guilisasti
exchanged notes on the exercise of consular functions in Macao by
Chile's Consulate General in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
