mission from the United States had business meetings with
representatives of high-level Hong Kong companies here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Led by John E. Mcphee, acting deputy assistant secretary for
technology and aerospace industries, the delegation composed of
computer companies selected by the U.S. Department of Commerce
arrived here Tuesday on a 10-day visit to China.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, the delegation heard briefings on the Hong
Kong information technology (IT) market given respectively by Dr.
James Liu, executive officer for the Hong Kong Industrial
Technology Center Corporation, Philip Leung, vice-president and
managing director of the Compaq Computer Hong Kong Ltd., and K.T.
Yung, general manager of Computer Services Division of the Hong
Kong Productivity Council.
</P>
<P>
Yung said that Hong Kong is one of the most developed IT market
in the region and its IT spending per capita is second to Japan
and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The IT market size (vendor revenue) was valued at 1,802 million
U.S. dollars in 1997, with an estimated growth of 11 percent this
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Yung said that Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region, emphasizes the importance of IT and
promotes IT application in the arena of education by allocating
more resources to primary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
Liu spoke of the strength of Hong Kong in the area of
technology development while Leung dwelled on the opportunities
and challenges in the Hong Kong IT market. 
