<HEADLINE> Norway Urges Progress at Washington Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut
Vollebaek urged the Palestinians and Israelis to come up with
"frank" decisions at the upcoming Washington peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian minister made the appeal following his talks with
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Wednesday on developments of
the Middle East peace process in light of the London meeting.
</P>
<P>
The back-to-back talks Palestinian and Israeli leaders had with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright have failed to produce
any real progress on the ground except promises of more talks in
Washington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek said he agrees with his Egyptian counterpart on the
importance of achieving some progress ahead of the U.S.-sponsored
Washington talks.
</P>
<P>
"What matters is that the Palestinians and Israelis should head
for Washington carrying frank positions vis-a-vis the American
ideas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is known to be demanding Israeli withdrawal from 13.1
percent of the West Bank, a proposal already accepted by the
Palestinian National Authority but rejected by the Israeli
government, which sticks to a 9-percent ceiling.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek spoke of Egypt's effective and positive stand to push
forward the Arab-Israeli peace talks, adding that Norway is also
assisting in bridging gaps between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
During their talks Wednesday, the two ministers tackled means
of activating the U.S.-brokered Oslo accords, which were signed by
the Palestinians and Israelis in 1993 in the Norwegian capital as
the cornerstone of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian top diplomat arrived here Tuesday night on a
two-day visit to Egypt for talks with Moussa and President Hosni
Mubarak on Egyptian and European efforts to breathing life into
the deadlocked peace-making.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been stalled since
March 1997 over Israeli settlement expansion and long-delayed
troop withdrawal from the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
