<HEADLINE> China's Top Legislator Meets International Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China will further tighten the work
on legislation, law enforcement and judicial administration in
line with the basic policy of managing the country according to
law, Li Peng, chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, said here today.
</P>
<P>
This is aimed to provide a legal guarantee for the growth of
the country's socialist market economy, Li said, in a meeting with
24 executive committee members of the International Association of
Prosecutors (IAP), who are here to enhance international
cooperation and effective crime-fighting methods.
</P>
<P>
He said China values the socialist law-building and takes it as
a basic condition and important guarantee to promote the reform
and opening-up, as well as the modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Li said the NPC is the most powerful state organ in China which
takes charge of the country's legislation. "We'll continue to
accelerate and improve legislation, and tighten the
post-legislative supervision," he said.
</P>
<P>
The NPC will also urge relevant departments to earnestly
implement law enforcement and the judicial administration, and to
fight crime in an effective way, he said.
</P>
<P>
The top legislator said that he wished the ongoing executive
committee meeting success in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Li said China supports its prosecutors' departments and
societies to encourages them to closely cooperate with their
international counterparts and to play a positive role in the IAP
for a concerted crime-fighting effort.
</P>
<P>
The Society of Public Prosecutors of China has decided to host
the Fourth IAP Conference in Beijing in September of 1999. Li said
China will offer full support for the conference.
</P>
<P>
Eamonn Barnes, president of the IAP executive committee, said
he appreciated China's promise to further strengthen cooperation
with its international counterparts to fight crimes.
</P>
<P>
This is also the basic goal of the IAP, he said, adding that
his organization thanks China for its efforts to make possible the
meeting being held in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhubin, Procurator-General of the Supreme People's
Procuratorate, was present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The non-governmental organization, founded in Vienna in June of
1995, urges all prosecutors throughout the world to effectively
prosecute criminals, crack down on internationally organized crime
and implement repatriation treaties.
</P>
<P>
A total of 27 senior Chinese prosecutors have joined the
association.  
</P>
</TEXT>
