<HEADLINE> Karpov to Play Exhibition Chess in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- World chess champion Anatoly Karpov
of Russia will visit China again and play exhibition chess with
Chinese grandmasters and youth players next week.
</P>
<P>
Karpov, five-time world champion, was invited by Chinese Chess
Association and will fly to Beijing next Monday for a 12-day tour
through China.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old Russian came to China first last August and had
a series exhibition matches with Chinese players.
</P>
<P>
He was scheduled to play a timed one-against-four competition
against Chinese women grandmasters, including World Women Junior
champion Zhu Chen, with 2,490 ranking points, and World Women
university champion Wang Lei, with 2,390.
</P>
<P>
The other two contenders are Qin Kanying (2,375) and Wang Pin
(2,370). Former world women champion Xie Jun will not compete in
the showing games.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, Karpov will vie with Chinese top four men
grandmasters, being led by seven-time Chinese national champion Ye
Jiangchuang (2,530).
</P>
<P>
Then Karpov will travel to Shanghai, Guangzhou of Guangdong
Province and Shenyang of Liaoning Province for a series games with
youth chess players.
</P>
<P>
Karpov, who pocketed the world title for the first time in
1975, successed in defending his crown after he beat Indian
challenger Viswanathan Anand in a fierce eight-game competition in
January in Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
