<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebels Kill Policemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Tamil rebels Wednesday
shot dead three policemen and attacked army positions in Northern
province of the country, ending a ceasefire to mark a visit by a
UN envoy, police sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the rebels ambushed the policemen from
Chettikulam in the district of Vavuniya, where UN envoy Olaara
Otunna was visiting.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels Sunday announced a two-day (Wednesday and
Thursday) unilateral ceasefire to coincide with the UN official's
visit to the northern regions.
</P>
<P>
A Sri Lankan Defense Ministry spokesman Monday dismissed the
rebel truce as a gimmick, citing an earlier truce broken by the
Tamil rebels in April, 1995 after 100 days.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting a war for a separate state
in the north and east of the country since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The latest fighting between government forces and the Tamil
rebels began on April 19, 1995 when the rebels blasted navy
gunboats at Trincomalee signaling an end to a cease-fire and peace
talks with the government. 
</P>
