<HEADLINE> Asia Society Annual Conference Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The ninth annual International
Corporate Conference of the Asia Society opened here Wednesday
evening, starting to address the long-term implications of the
economic crisis for the political, social and strategic challenges
Asia is facing.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif is to deliver the opening
address.
</P>
<P>
According to Asia Society President Nicholas Platt, a report
will be released during the final session of the three-day
conference.
</P>
<P>
The report will include the findings of a group of Asian and
American statesmen and business leaders "from diverse backgrounds
to take a long look out over the horizon."
</P>
<P>
It is an opportunity for business executives and government
leaders to step aside from the turmoil in the Asian economies and
look to the future of business in the region and around the world,
Platt said at a pre-conference news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Keynote speakers of the conference include Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, Deputy
Prime Minister Pham Gia Khiem of Vietnam, Deputy Minister of
Finance and Economy Chung Duck-koo of the Republic of Korea, Vice
Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Long Yongtu of
China, and President Mitsuo Sato of the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 800 participants will assess the effects of the
return of Hong Kong to China ten months ago, and they will examine
specific proposals for policy reforms, including fundamental
changes in investment and business practices intended to set the
stage for sustainable growth in the region.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by the Asia Society, Dow Jones &AMP;
Company, in cooperation with Hong Kong Trade Development Council
and Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1956, the U.S.-based Asia Society is dedicated to
fostering public understanding of Asia and communication between
the United States and Asia-Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The previous eight conferences were held in Hong Kong, Bali,
Taipei, Tokyo, Singapore, Beijing, Seoul and New Delhi,
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
