<HEADLINE> Worldwide Prosecutors Meet to Discuss Ways to Combat Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. prosecutor said today that he
felt no fear walking in the streets of Beijing at 6 a.m. with his
wife, something he could not do in New York City.
</P>
<P>
John Kaye, who was attending the executive committee meeting of
the International Association of Prosecutors (IAP) here,
said: "The government in China is very strong about order and rule
of law."
</P>
<P>
The IAP's 24 executive members are meeting in Beijing to
enhance international cooperation and seek effective methods to
deal with crime.
</P>
<P>
The non-governmental organization, established in June of 1995
in Vienna, urged prosecutors throughout the world to effectively
prosecute criminals, crack down on internationally organized crime
and implement repatriation treaties.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven Chinese senior procurators have joined the
association. In addition, China will host the Fourth IAP
Conference in Beijing in September of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to walk toward a uniform approach to the
operation of prosecuting," said Kaye, president of the National
District Attorney Association in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The association should develop worldwide standards of
performance that will protect the profits and property of
international businesses. It's very important that these companies
are treated fairly no matter where they are," he said.
</P>
<P>
High-ranking prosecutors at the meeting put combating organized
crime high on their priority list.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people feel that the only victims of organized crime
are those who get involved with robberies, prostitution or drug
use," Kaye said. "But that is not true. Organized crime actually
attacks everybody."
</P>
<P>
Kittipong Kittayarak from Thailand said that China has a good
judicial system and effective legal bodies.
</P>
<P>
"China has made great progress in fighting crime. And it's very
good for your country to take fighting economic crime as a
priority," said Kittayarak, executive director of the Institute of
Criminal Law of the Attorney General of Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
