<HEADLINE> Veteran Thai Politician Chatichai Dies of Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Thai prime minister and
leader of Thailand's Chart Pattana Party Chatichai Choonhavan died
of cancer in London Wednesday morning, news reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The 78-year-old veteran politician, who went for England four
weeks ago and undergone a second intestine cancer operation in
London, died at 0955 GMT (4:55 p.m. Bangkok time).
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai expressed his condolences over
Chatichai's death and said the ongoing cabinet meeting stopped one
minute for mourning.
</P>
<P>
Chatichai was elected prime minister in August 1988. When in
office, he maintained Thailand's successful status as a newly
industrialized country and was also active in foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, a military coup d'etat ousted the democratically
elected Chatichai cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chatichai was also the leader of the Chart Pattana Party, which
is the third largest political party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a Chart Pattana Party senior official said that the
party will select a new party leader this month.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chart Pattana Party leader Korn Dabaransi, who is also
Chatichai's nephew, said Chatichai's body will be sent back home
as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
