<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China, Kazakhstan Expand Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The six years since China and
Kazakhstan established diplomatic ties have witnessed a rapid
development of their good-neighbor relations, with trade and
economic cooperation growing year after year.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming visit to China by Kazakh Prime Minister Nurlan
Utebovich Balgimbaev, beginning on Thursday, will add a new
impetus to the bilateral relations and cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
Sharing a 1,700-kilometer-long border, the two countries will
take full advantage of their geographic convenience to speed up
their economic reforms and opening up to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors can benefit immensely from cooperation. While
Kazakhstan can supply oil, natural gas, non-ferrous metals and
other raw materials badly needed for China's modernization drive,
China can supply industrial products, especially consumer goods,
to Kazakhstan and serve as a convenient outlet of the landlocked
country to the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Under the care of their leaders, the two countries have signed
a series of economic and trade agreements to boost trade, protect
investment, and cooperate in banking, transport and oil
production. They have also set up an inter-governmental committee
to facilitate economic, trade and scientific cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In fact, their trade and economic cooperation have expanded
steadily over the years. Two-way trade, which was 336 million
U.S. dollars in 1994, rose to 527 million dollars in 1997. It is
expected to reach one billion dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
A major investor in Kazakhstan, China has set up 375 businesses
there, with a total investment of 320 million dollars. The
Chinese-funded enterprises are operating in the fields of oil
production, farm product processing, leather processing and
catering business.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Kazakhstan has established 15 businesses in
the neighboring Chinese ethnic region of Xinjiang, becoming the
fourth largest foreign investor there. Their business operations
cover leather processing, construction materials and auto repairs.
</P>
<P>
Businesses from the two countries are also exploring the
possibility to cooperate in auto-making, textile industry,
telecommunications and construction.
</P>
<P>
The year 1997 represented a landmark in their relations.
Chinese Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier Li Lanqing visited the
central Asian country in September, giving a strong push to the
cooperation between the two countries. In June, China's
state-owned oil company won the tenders to develop oil and gas in
Aktyubinsk and Uzen, two of Kazakhstan's major oil and gas
fields. In September, the two sides formally signed three
agreements on oil and gas cooperation, which were described as the
"contracts of the century" by Kazakh President N. A. Nazarbayev.
</P>
<P>
As the president noted, the cooperation in oil and gas will
help spur the overall development of the relations between the two
neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Why China Is Restructuring its Grain Marketing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Local analysts observe that the
announcement Wednesday by the Chinese government on the
restructuring of the grain marketing system is of great importance
to the country's long-term grain security.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji, speaking at a national conference on
the issue, said that it is "inevitable and urgent" to carry out the
reform.
</P>
<P>
An official with the State Development Planning Commission told
Xinhua today that the existing grain circulation system in China
has been increasingly unsuited to the country's grain production,
and the changes in grain supply and demand.
</P>
<P>
Farmers find it difficult to sell their grain in good harvest
years, while grain prices soar in poor harvest years, the official
said, stressing that this contradiction must be resolved.
</P>
<P>
The official held that China's per capita grain output stands
at less than 400 kg, though the country ranks first in the world
in grain production, which has resulted in a long-time
imbalance of grain supply and demand in the country.
</P>
<P>
Under the current circumstances, the operation of the grain
circulation system plays an important role in grain production and
consumption, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The main problems in China's grain marketing system lie in the
fact that the state-owned grain companies play a dual role of both
storage and marketing, with a managerial mechanism that has failed
to operate in line with the laws governing market operation and
has resulted in severe financial losses, according to some local
experts.
</P>
<P>
For decades, China's grain firms have mixed government
functions and commercial roles, with the result that they have
been suffering from bad debts and financial losses for many years.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the state grain firms are trapped by planned
economy structures; they do not have the authority to make
managerial decisions on their own, and suffer from overstaffing,
high operation costs and poor economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that state grain companies have lost
more than 100 billion yuan in the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
More important is the fact that nearly half of the country's
grain has been sold to consumers by state firms. The poor
operation of these companies has made it very difficult for them
to guide grain prices, and for the government to regulate the
grain market and fight against hazards there.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the grain production capacity in different
provinces varies remarkably, while the country's grain market as a
whole is immature. As a result, local governments depend heavily
on the central government for grain supplies, and problems often
crop up between local governments regarding grain purchases and
sales.
</P>
<P>
To tackle these problems, the central government Wednesday
announced the "four principles and one improvement" policy for the
restructuring of state grain companies, namely, separation of
functions of the government from those of enterprise functions,
storage from managerial functions, responsibilities of central
government from those of local governments, and new from old
accounts, and improvement of the grain pricing system.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has worked out concrete measures to carry out
the reform based on these principles, and these measures will be
announced soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Travel Agency Network Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China's largest travel agency
network was established here today, with the head office of China
International Travel Service (CITS) as the core.
</P>
<P>
The network of 120 members is expected to be the strongest
force in the country's tourism sector. The move is designed to
alleviate the effects of the Southeast Asia financial crisis,
currency devaluations in some European countries and the fierce
competition among domestic travel agencies, said Li Lu'an,
president of the CITS head office.
</P>
<P>
Network members will consolidate cooperation, conduct business
with a single image and the same service standard, and seek
tourism sources for others in an effort to attract more tourists.
</P>
<P>
The CITS group was set up in 1989, but group members did not
link assets nor have any regular internal operating mechanism or
rules.
</P>
<P>
The travel agencies have been working toward joint air and
railway transport networks in the last few years. CITS group is
now preparing to pass its ISO9000 quality certification
examination.
</P>
<P>
The CITS head office, the country's largest travel agency,
handled 533,000 overseas tourists last year, representing a
year-on-year rise of 10.7 percent. Other CITS members also
reported good performances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
