<HEADLINE> G-15 to Prepare for South-North Summit With G-7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Group-15 of developing countries
will prepare for a summit meeting with the G-7, a club of the
world's leading industrialized countries, the Middle East News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, now grouping 16 developing countries, will convene
its eighth summit in Cairo on May 11-13, only days before the G-7
holds its own summit in Birmingham, Britain, in the middle of this
month.
</P>
<P>
Among topics to be raised at the G-15 Cairo summit is a message
from the G-15 to the G-7 to examine means of entering a dialog at
various levels with the ultimate goal of holding a summit of the
two groups, according to well-informed sources.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has sent a message containing
the proposal to British Prime Minister Tony Blair, whose countries
now holds the rotating presidency of European Union presidency and
the G-7.
</P>
<P>
His message addressed economic worries of the developing
countries and their wish to open a constructive dialog with the
seven major industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 summit is to discuss political and economic issues
including Asian countries' financial crisis, cooperation between
member states and activation of North-South dialog.
</P>
<P>
It will offer opportunities to the member states to take stock
of the recent developments of the world economy, formulate a
unified stand on global economic order and forge constructive
dialog with developed countries.
</P>
<P>
As a group of developing countries from Latin America, Africa
and Asia, the G-15 was founded in 1989. Kenya became the 16th
member last year, joining Egypt, India, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Algeria, Zimbabwe, Senegal, Nigeria, Argentina, Jamaica,
Venezuela, Mexico, Brazil, Peru and Chile.
</P>
<P>
Seven heads of state, three vice presidents and a number of
ministers are expected at the summit, in which they will issue a
communique spelling out the group's stances on economic and
political issues.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the summit, trade ministers and foreign
ministers of the G-15 will convene their separate meetings here
this week.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members, accounting for 30 percent of the world's
population and 27 percent of the land area of the third world,
represent the emerging economies of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
Their total gross domestic product makes up 39 percent of the
third world and exports, 31 percent of the developing countries'
total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
