<HEADLINE> S. African Moslems Dismayed at Visa Refusal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Moslem community of South
Africa on Wednesday expressed shock at the reluctance of the
South African government to issue visas to Hamas spiritual leader
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin.
</P>
<P>
Yassin was reportedly refused a visa last week, and Moslems'
hope of him meeting President Nelson Mandela during his South
African visit this week was dashed Tuesday when a presidential
aide said Mandela had no plans for the meeting, South African
Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The welcoming committee for Yassin said in a statement that
Yassin was invited by the South African Moslem community as part
of his international tour.
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to the South African government to consider our
request that Sheikh Yassin be allowed to set foot on South
African soil, especially in view of the fact that his trip is a
private one," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"President Mandela has since his inauguration maintained an
open policy and indicated that he would be willing to meet Hamas
at some point in the future," it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African Moslem condemned the "interference by
the Palestinian National Authority in attempting to stop" Yassin's
visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of political opportunism flies in the face of the
expressed unity and cooperation between the Palestinian National
Authority and Hamas," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
News reports earlier this week said the Palestinian Authority
of Yasser Arafat had apparently exerted pressure on the South
African government to prohibit Yassin from visiting.
</P>
<P>
Last month, South African Justice Minister Dullah Omar and
Constitutional Affairs Minister Valli Moosa met Yassin while they
were in Saudi Arabia to attend the annual haj, or pilgrimage, to
Mecca.
</P>
<P>
Hamas' military wing has been responsible for a series of
suicide bombings in Israel over the past decade, which claimed
scores of Israeli lives. Yassin was released from an Israeli jail
last year in exchange for Israeli commandos held in Jordan.
</P>
