<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Population Ages Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's population is ageing
faster than any country's in the history of the world, according
to a news release from the United Nations Development Program
received Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The report estimates that over the next two decades Sri Lanka's
workforce will shrink, while the number of the elderly will
double. By the year 2025 Sri Lanka will stand alone as the only
non-high income country with an elderly population greater than 20
percent
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's population will stabilize at 21 million before
2025.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Sri Lankans are 25 years old on average but, by
2025, that median age is expected to jump to 40, and reach 50 in
less than 60 years, the report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of the population over 60 years will increase
rapidly from 8 percent currently, to reach 13 percent in 2010 and
20 percent in 2025, said the report, adding that inevitably this
will mean a drastic increase of old age dependency.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's successful family planning programs and efficient
health services, coupled with economic factors, have also made a
significant impact on the country's current demographic changes,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Plenum of Macao SARPC Issues Communique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The First Plenum of the Preparatory
Committee for the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR)
of the National People's Congress closed here today, with the
issuing of a communique. The full text of the communique is as
follows:
</P>
<P>
The First Plenum of the Preparatory Committee for the
Macao Special Administrative Region of the National People's
Congress was held in Beijing May 5-6.
</P>
<P>
Senior Communist Party of China (CPC) and state leaders Jiang
Zemin, Li Peng, Zhu Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao, Wei Jianxing
and Li Lanqing met with all the Preparatory Committee
members. Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the Central Committee
of the CPC and Chinese president, delivered an important speech at
the meeting, which was presided over by Xie Fei, vice-chairman of
the Preparatory Committee. Qian Qichen, chairman of the
Preparatory Committee, made speeches, respectively, at the opening
and closing meetings.
</P>
<P>
The plenum discussed and approved the work rules of the
Preparatory Committee, set up four working groups to handle
political, legal, economic and social and cultural affairs,
respectively, and held an earnest discussion on the future work of
the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
The plenum holds that the establishment of the Preparatory
Committee of the Macao SAR marked the start of a new phase in the
preparations for resuming the exercise of sovereignty by the
Chinese government over Macao.
</P>
<P>
Preparatory Committee members will solicit opinions of people
from all walks of life in Macao and engage in all kinds of
preparations for the founding of the Macao SAR in accordance with
the Basic Law of the Macao SAR and relevant decisions of the
National People's Congress and its Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The plenum maintains that the resumption of exercise of
sovereignty over Macao by the Chinese government on December 20,
1999, will be another grand event after the return of Hong Kong to
the motherland last year. This is of great significance to the
long-term stability and development of Macao and the eventual
realization of the complete reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
All Preparatory Committee members, fully aware of the heavy
responsibilities they shoulder, expressed their determination to
live up to the expectations of the people of ethnic groups across
China, including the Macao compatriots, and strive to fulfill all
the tasks of the Preparatory Committee.
</P>
<P>
The second plenum of the Preparatory Committee is due to be
held here July 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
