<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Drop on Foreign Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Late buying saw the Australian
sharemarket close off its lows, brought on by negative sentiment
from the weaker overnight U.S. market and easing on Asian markets
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 15.5 points to 2788.0, with
mining stocks particularly weak.
</P>
<P>
"You had the easing of the Dow Jones last night and the easing
on the Asian markets today and the combination of those led our
market down today," Jack Moss from Shaw Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones slipped 45.09 points overnight to 9147.57 on
concerns about more talk of an interest rate rise after a meeting
between Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan and U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, the Nikkei index dropped 357.26 points to 15,243.84
on fading chances of an income tax easing and fresh concerns about
the financial system.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index fell 25.4 points to 4787.2.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks were relatively steady. ANZ lost 1.3 cents,
National Australia improved 4.3 cents, Westpac shed a cent while
Commonwealth lost 6.8 cents.
</P>
<P>
Insurance and banking giant AMP released its prospectus ahead
of listing, but the news was not enough to significantly affect
the market.
</P>
<P>
News Corp lost three cents while the preferred shares dropped
five cents.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Patrick stevedores' parent Lang Corp closed steady
with the outcome of the dock dispute still uncertain.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 7.7 points, with commodity
exporters failing to respond to the lower dollar. Rio Tinto was 24
cents stronger but most of the majors posted falls.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 18.4 points to 1338.6, as the bullion price
closed in Sydney at 303.55 U.S. dollars, from 303.75 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 266.78 million shares at a value of
761.24 million Australian dollars (487.19 million U.S. dollars),
with falls outnumbering rises 728 to 393. 
</P>
</TEXT>
