<HEADLINE> Nigerian Legislators Join Abacha Persuasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's newly-elected state and
national legislators have joined the campaign aimed at persuading
the military leader, General Sani Abacha to transform himself
into a civilian president this October.
</P>
<P>
The legislators, under the umbrella of the "Union of
Democratically-Elected Representatives of Nigerians", will meet
on the issue Thursday in Abuja, the Nigerian capital.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, the meeting is expected to pass a
resolution calling on Abacha to accept the invitation of the
country's five political parties to have him as their consensus
candidate in the presidential election scheduled for August.
</P>
<P>
Senator Arthur Nzeribe, the co-ordinator of the group, told
newsmen in Abuja Tuesday that the resolution will be forwarded to
all foreign missions and embassies for onward transmission to
their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
The legislators will also proceed on a peace march to the Aso
Rock presidential villa to present their resolution to General
Abacha, the co-ordinator said.
</P>
<P>
Nzeribe said that "General Abacha saved this country from
disintegrating and we now have a hope and a vision for the future
via the Vision 2010 which was put together by some of the best
brains."
</P>
<P>
He argued that "there is nothing wrong with the sequential
call on General Abacha to contest the presidential election, in
the interest of Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
Nzeribe, however, advised Abacha to contest the presidential
election as a civilian.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's special adviser, former Internal Affairs Minister
Wada Nas has said that Abacha will contest as "General Abacha".
</P>
</TEXT>
