<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Jetfoil Might Have Hit Ship Wreck in Crash: Fisherman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A fisherman reportedly said that
the Macao-bound Hong Kong jetfoil, which crashed Saturday
afternoon, might have hit the wreck of a sunken ship, Hong Kong
newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The crash of the Far East jetfoil "Flores" occurred some 1.6
kilometers off Tai O at Hong Kong's largest island Lantau, leaving
120 passengers and crew members injured. A seriously wounded old
woman died in hospital early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The jetfoil was believed to have hit an unidentified underwater
object in the accident.
</P>
<P>
Vessels with sonar detecting equipment and divers sent by the
Hong Kong Marine Department had been searching the scene to find
anything submerged in the water which might be related to the
accident.
</P>
<P>
The department had called on witnesses to come forward to help
the on-going investigation.
</P>
<P>
A fisherman named Chan Ma-sing said he was fishing with his
family when he saw the damaged jetfoil directly above the wreck of
a 90-meter-long ship that sank six years ago. He believed the
vessel hit the wreck even though he did not hear any loud noise at
the time.
</P>
<P>
All fishermen in these waters knew where the wreck was and the
driver of the jetfoil should also know the location as the wreck
had been marked on Hong Kong marine charts, said Chan, who has
been fishing in the area for more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The wreck is 1.5 nautical miles (2.4 kilometers) north of the
location of the accident given by the jetfoil's captain and lies
off the jetfoil's route, one of the three approved routes for Far
East jetfoils, according to Marine Department officials.
</P>
<P>
Although the wreck is quite far from the reported crash site,
Marine Department officials said they would check the wreck to see
whether it had been hit.
</P>
<P>
Other experts had held that the vessel might have hit garbage
such as parcels from abandoned boats, logs and furniture, which
had been found floating or submerged in the waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
