<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Lower, Resting up for Big Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar rested up
Wednesday, closing little changed and marginally lower.
</P>
<P>
Thursday brings a busy day for the local currency with the
release of April labor force figures and the semi-annual statement
by Reserve Bank of Australia Governor Ian Macfarlane.
</P>
<P>
The local session closed at 64.10 U.S. cents, from 64.14 late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar has stayed in a very tight range ahead
of the monetary policy statement and the employment figures
tomorrow," a Commonwealth Bank dealer said.
</P>
<P>
"The currency is just waiting to see what Mr. Macfarlane has to
say on the economy and draw some inference from that on monetary
policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Macfarlane will speak before the House of Representatives
Standing Committee on Financial Institutions and Public
Administration in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics will release labor force
figures Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Employment fell by a seasonally adjusted 15,500 in March, from
February's rise of 14,800. The March unemployment rate rose to a
seasonally adjusted 8.2 percent, from 8.1 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
Market expectations for April employment center on a rise of
25,000 and range from a rise of 10,000 to 40,000. Forecasts for
the unemployment rate range from 8.0 percent to 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 84.85 from 85.37 against the
Japanese yen, and at 1.1359 from 1.1431 against the Deutsche mark.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
