<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Coroner Calls for Ban on PU Foam Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong inquest coroner has
called for an immediate withdrawal from market all products made
of PU foam, according to a Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In his report on last year's Mei Foo Sun Chuen fire which was
released here Tuesday, Ian Thomas listed recommendations on
improving fire safety. Nine people died in the fire.
</P>
<P>
He recommended, among other things, that all furniture and
mattresses made of PU foam be withdrawn from the market in Hong
Kong and that import of such items be banned.
</P>
<P>
PU foam, a petroleum by-product in the form of plastic foam, is
mainly used for the production of mattresses, upholstered cushions
and furniture fillings.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has legislative control on all consumer goods,
including PU foam furniture. The Consumer Goods Safety Ordinance,
which came into effect in late 1995, imposes a statutory
responsibility on manufacturers, importers and suppliers to ensure
that consumer goods supplied for private use are safe. The
ordinance created a "general safety requirement" and specified the
reasonable level of safety required of different consumer goods,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that PU foam is not one of the listed dangerous
goods under the Dangerous Goods Ordinance, which provides for the
control on potentially hazardous substances. PU foam is not
recognized as dangerous goods according to international standards
prescribed under the International Maritime Dangerous Goods Code.
</P>
<P>
Special legislation on the control of PU foam products is not
common, with the only such cases in Britain and the United States,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government is considering other
recommendations in the coroner's report, such as the importance of
the proper operation and maintenance of fire safety installations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
