<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Angolan Troops in Congo (B) Withdrawn: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo Dos Santos
has said that "most" of Angolan troops sent to Congo
(Brazzaville) in 1997 have been withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
President Dos Santos disclosed this at the press conference he
jointly held with the visiting Congolese President Sassou Nguesso
in Luanda Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan president said that a "phased" withdrawal plan is
being carried out until all the Angolan troops leave the Republic
of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are discussing matters concerning bilateral
military cooperation, including the issue of officer training
offered by Angola, said Dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
As for this, President Sassou Nguesso on his one-day visit to
Angola said that the Angolan troops remaining in Congo can
participate in the establishment and training of the Congolese
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Angolan troops for their assistance in solving
the military conflict in his country.
</P>
<P>
As to the situation back in home, President Sassou Nguesso
said that generally speaking, peace has been realized after a
period of recovery, particularly in the Capital city of
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Now, weapon collection has begun across the country, said the
president.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 when conflict broke out in Congo, Angola sent
thousands of its troops there, contributing a lot to the
reinstatement of Sassou Nguesso as Congolese president.
</P>
<P>
President Sassou Nguesso arrived in Luanda for a short visit.
This is his second visit to the country since he returned to
power in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
Last October, the Congolese president came to Luanda to attend
the four-side summit of Angola, Congo, Gabon and the Democratic
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
