<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feasibility Study on Trans-Asia Railway Ready in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Transport Minister
Ling Liong Sik said Wednesday the feasibility study on the
Trans-Asia Railway from Singapore to Kunming, China, is expected
to be ready next month.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the study conducted by Malaysia would be the
basis for the implementation of the project which was approved at
the 5th ASEAN summit in Bangkok on December 15, 1995, he said in
parliament, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Once the feasibility study is ready, it would be tabled at the
ASEAN heads of government meeting and the possibility is that the
meeting would invite an international consortium to implement the
project.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has allocated 2 million ringgit (about
0.53 million U.S. dollars) for the feasibility study while the
consortium involved would pay 3 million ringgit (about 0.795
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The estimated cost of the project could only be decided after
the engineering study is done, the minister said, adding the
engineering study would include topography, detailed engineering
designs, compliance with minimum standards and also the estimated
cost of building the tracks and the choice of route.
</P>
<P>
Ling said the consultants were considering several routes
including
(1) Singapore-Malaysia-Thailand-Cambodia-Vietnam direct to
Kunming,
(2) Singapore-Malaysia-Thailand-Laos with connection in Vietnam,
(3) Singapore-Malaysia-Thailand-Laos direct to China, and (4)
Singapore-Malaysia-Myanmar and from Myanmar direct to China.
</P>
<P>
He said that for Malaysia, the existing railway lines could be
used and there would be no extra cost for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
