<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNAIDS Shows Concern for "Youth in Shadow of AIDS" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations official has asked
for a global effort to help young people around the world "out of
the shadow of AIDS."
</P>
<P>
"Young people today grow up in the shadow of AIDS (because) new
infections in them are occuring at the rate of five per minute,"
said Peter Piot, executive director of the Joint United Nations
Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), in an interview with Xinhua New
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Adolescents should be entitled to concern in HIV/AIDS
campaigns, not only because they were particularly important for
society, but also because they have been seriously affected by the
epidemic, said Piot today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
UNAIDS reported that more than half of new infections with HIV,
the human immunodeficiency virus which causes acquired immune
deficiency syndrome (AIDS), are occurring in the 10-24 age group
each year. Those who have dropped out of school, who live on
the streets, share needles with other drug users or engage in
commercial sex are especially vulnerable to HIV infections, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"That's why UNAIDS has chosen to focus the 1998 World AIDS
Campaign on young people," Piot said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign would encourage more adolescents to participate in
HIV/AIDS control efforts, and offer help and care to HIV victims.
</P>
<P>
"Furthermore, young people are not just a target group for
action, but also a force for change," he said, commenting
favorably on an essay competition on "Adolescents and AIDS" which
concluded Tuesday in Beijing. Some 600 students participated in
the essay contest.
</P>
<P>
Piot, 49, devoted himself to HIV/AIDS research for a dozen
years before his appointment as director of UNAIDS, established in
1996 by the United Nations as a leader of the global campaign
against AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
