<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Raps U.S. Weak Stand in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian permanent delegate to
the Arab League said Wednesday that a "weak" U.S. stance has led
to the failure of the London meetings and overcast the peace talks
in Washington next week.
</P>
<P>
In statements to the middle East News Agency, Mohamed Sobeih
expressed pessimism over another round of back-to-back talks
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to have with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in Washington next Monday.
</P>
<P>
"My pessimism is attributed to the hostile and antagonistic
stance by Israeli Premier Netanyahu vis-a-vis the Oslo Agreement,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Going to Washington, following a similar round of meetings in
London last Monday and Tuesday, are meant to give time to all
parties including the U.S. administration and the Palestinian and
Israeli leaderships to flesh out an acceptable solution to break
out of the 14-month deadlock in peace-making.
</P>
<P>
"Time is a pressing element to the Palestinians," Sobeih added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side accepted the U.S. ideas which talked among
other things of an Israeli withdrawal from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank, freezing of any unilateral step, and calling for a
third Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Israel did not respond to these ideas, shirking off the
withdrawal from the 13.1 percent but the U.S. stance was not firm
in this respect," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said failure to reach an agreement to implement the
U.S. initiative is "nothing but a reluctance on the Israeli side
and a kind of laxity on the U.S. side."
</P>
<P>
Albright is known seeking Israeli approval of a further
pullback of 13 percent from the West Bank, an interim withdrawal
proposal acceptable to Arafat but shunned by Netanyahu who has
offered no more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the London meetings, Netanyahu's adviser said the
Israeli premier was not empowered to redeploy forces in more than
9 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official termed the U.S. stance as weak, citing
the fact that neither Albright nor U.S. Mideast peace coordinator
Dennis Ross who came to the Mideast in the last week of April,
made public the new U.S. ideas.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that "in the end, the entire issue
remains the U.S. administration's responsibility if it really want
to realize peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
Arafat will make a full assessment of the peace process on the
Palestinian-Israeli track with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
here on Thursday, said the Palestinian delegate to the Cairo-based
Arab League.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
1997 over Israeli settlement buildings and long-delayed military
withdrawal from the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
