<HEADLINE> Zambia Takes Measures to Increase Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
lUSAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) --The Zambia Revenues Authority (ZRA)
Wednesday announced measures to increase revenues so as to reach
the country's 1998 target estimated at 1,090 billion Kwacha or 700
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held at the State House, ZRA Commissioner
General Kevin Donovan said that the authority, among other
measures, will widen the country's tax base and curb smuggling
and undervaluation of imported goods.
</P>
<P>
Donovan said that ZRA will be mounting an operation to get
local Zambians working for foreign embassies expatriate staff
into the country's tax net since these people have never paid tax
to the revenues institution.
</P>
<P>
He warned that these people should "come immediately" to pay
their income tax, otherwise they will "suffer the consequences."
</P>
<P>
Donovan said that in order to curb smuggling, ZRA will deploy
more special teams to monitor imported goods.
</P>
<P>
Most of the smuggled goods, including foodstuff and cooking
oil, came from South Africa and Zimbabwe, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past years since ZRA was established in 1993, Zambia's
revenues have steadily increasing from 421 billion Kwacha (300
million Dollars) in 1994 to 954 billion Kwacha last year.
</P>
<P>
Though this year's target is difficult to acheive,
Donovan expressed his optimistic over ZRA's performance since in
the first quarter of this year, it collected 248 billion Kwacha
(170 million Dollars) against a target of 229 billion Kwacha (160
million Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
