<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biotech Immature for Developing Nations to Combat Grain Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- It will take some time for
developing nations to use biotechnology as an effective weapon
against insufficient rain, said scientists today at a conference
on life sciences in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Biotechnology is playing a major role in combating global grain
shortages as high and new technologies in the field are quickly
spreading around the world, especially in Western nations, said
Professor Ray Wu of Cornell University in the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, developing nations must overcome problems in
funding scientific research and other systematic shortcomings
before biotechnology itself can help reduce grain shortages.
</P>
<P>
As famines and grain shortages pose a great threat to humans,
most countries have targeted biotechnology as an important part of
its scientific research, according to scientists attending the
conference.
</P>
<P>
In the developed world, said Professor Wu, genetically
engineered crops able to resist cold, disease and insects through
inheritance are already planted in small experimental fields, and
more varieties are expected to become popular within the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
However, developing nations, the main victims of grain
shortages, have to import new crop varieties from abroad because
of insufficient funding to support their own research.
</P>
<P>
Some experts believe the developing world's reliance on the
developed nations will make the latter the greatest beneficiary of
progress in biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
Professor Zhou Zengquan of the School of Life Sciences of
Beijing University, said that increased international cooperation,
especially that between developed and developing countries, to
close the gaps existing in biotechnological research is of great
significance to global stability and development.
</P>
<P>
"Developing nations must put more emphasis on fund input and
personnel training in biotechnological research," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the omnipresent problem of fund shortages, he added,
inadequate allocation of the funding, meaning that money is not
funneled to the most important projects, is also a factor in the
scientific research gap between developed and developing
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
