<HEADLINE> Nurses in Indian Capital Continue their Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Health services in Indian capital
New Delhi remained paralyzed for the second day Wednesday as more
than 11,000 nurses continued their indefinite strike.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which started here Tuesday in 28 government
hospitals in the city, has been called by the Delhi Nurses Union
(DNU) to protest the alleged backtracking by the government on the
agreement signed with it last September on pay scales, promotion
and other demands.
</P>
<P>
The government said Tuesday that it was open for talks with the
agitating nurses in the capital over their demands, but ruled out
any pay hike. The striking nurses rejected the government's offer
for talks minus any hike in pay.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the DNU G. K. Khurana said Tuesday that
they would not relent until the government accepted all their
demands. Any attempt by the government to sabotage the strike by
bringing in students from the nursing schools would be resisted
tooth and nail, Khurana said. 
</P>
