<HEADLINE> Namibian Power Supplier Gets Loan From European </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Namibian electricity
supplier, Nampower, has secured a loan of 620 million Rand (124
million U.S. Dollars) from the European Development Bank (EDB) to
strengthen Namibia's electricity supply network.
</P>
<P>
The money will help fund a 880-million-Rand
(176-million-U.S.-Dollar) power line from Aries in South Africa
to Auas near Windhoek, South African Press Association (SAPA)
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the funding is to be raised by Nampower locally,
and the project will be completed by the year 2000, according to
SAPA.
</P>
<P>
Nampower Wednesday described the agreement with the EDB as one
of the biggest projects since Namibia's independence in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The main source of Namibian electrical power is the Ruacana
hydro-electricity station in the north. Unreliable rain patterns
and growing electricity demand will require additional supply in
the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
