<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Hainan Island, Land of Longevity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The average life span on China's
island province of Hainan is now 73.1 years, compared to a
national average of 70, thanks to a decade of health care work.
</P>
<P>
The semi-tropical island, with its coastal climate, has a good
environment that has been little affected by the island's becoming
China's fifth special economic zone 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The amount of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and dust in the air is
much lower than the nation's standard, and the amount of forest
coverage is above 50 percent, making it one of the top three
provinces in the field.
</P>
<P>
Before China was founded in 1949, the average life span of the
poverty-ridden island was only 35 years. From 1949 to 1987, the
island's economy was backward and spending on health care was very
low, recalls one local official, who explains that, at that time,
people were threatened by diseases like malaria, cholera, and
dengue fever, and before 1987, the incidence of infectious
diseases was three times the national average.
</P>
<P>
After it was designated a province in 1988, spending on health
care began to increase and, by the end of last year, it had nearly
2,000 hospitals and clinics, and more than 30,000 doctors. In
Haikou, the provincial capital, there are 9.1 doctors per 1,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
The official says that the local government has placed priority
on infectious diseases, and set up a special research institute of
tropical diseases, and diseases that have plagued the island for
years are now under control.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of urban residents are spending money to
use gyms and farmers in rural areas have gradually learned about
hygiene.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0176 </DOCNO>
