<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique: Cholera Under Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A Mozambican national health
official has announced that cholera is already under control in
the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, the situation in the whole country is stable," the
Noticias newspaper Wednesday quoted Avertino Barreto, Director
Assistant of the National Health Bureau, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Barreto Tuesday pointed out that cholera has come under
control as far as the whole nation is concerned, though there are
still places where the disease is spreading.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, some makeshift clinics have been closed and the
personnel invited to act as doctors and nurses have returned to
work in their own institutions and study in the training schools.
</P>
<P>
The medical institutions and medical schools across the
country have returned normal, said Barreto.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the past two days only two persons died of
cholera in the whole country and there were only 78 cholera cases
recorded.
</P>
<P>
"Since last August when cholera broke out, there have been 767
people dying of cholera and 33,781 more suffering from the
epidemic," said Barreto.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, this does not mean that the country can
relax their effort over the disease.
</P>
<P>
Barreto reminded that great care should be taken of personal
hygiene and preventive measures should not be abandoned without
the order of the Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
According to him, among the patients newly infected by
cholera, 46 are living in central Zambezia Province, 27 in Fofala
Province and five in the southern Gaza Province.
</P>
<P>
So far, of the 10 provinces in Mozambique, only three in the
north have not reported any cholera cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
