<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Resume Commercial Flights to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's National carrier, Royal
Jordanian (RJ), will begin resuming regular commercial flights to
Tehran, Iran, on June 15, after a hiatus of 18 years.
</P>
<P>
RJ Deputy Director General Majdi Sabri said here Wednesday that
the airlines will fly twice every week to and back from Tehran and
the flights mainly aim to serve religious tourists from Iran to
Islamic sites in Jordan, said Sabri.
</P>
<P>
The RJ has noticed that the number of Iranians coming to
Jordan to visit the sepulchers of some companions of Prophet
Mohammad increased by a large margin during the past two years, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The resumed flights will also accommodate businessmen shuttling
between the two countries, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, no Iranian airlines declared intention to fly to
Amman in the near future, said Sabri.
</P>
<P>
Flights between capital cities of the two countries stopped 18
years ago as Iran suspended political ties with the kingdom over
Jordan's tilt over Iraq during the Iraq-Iran war (1980-1988).
</P>
<P>
The two countries resumed ties in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
