<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Signs off Apollo Hotel Ltd. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has signed a
divestiture agreement with Ethiopia-based Midroc Tuesday, selling
80 percent shares in Apollo Hotel Corporation Limited.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, Midroc shall pay 19 million U.S. Dollars for
the offered shares in stages, the Monitor newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The buyer is also required to provide a performing bond of 1.9
million U.S. Dollars within 30 months.
</P>
<P>
"'The shareholders' agreement will only be signed on
completion of actions stated above and the management of the
hotel shall remain under ITT Sheraton," a press statement
released after the signing said.
</P>
<P>
Mayanja Nkangi, the Ugandan minister of finance who signed on
behalf of the government, urged the new owner of the hotel to
provide better service to customers.
</P>
<P>
"You have taken on the very best. We do not sell property to
be distributed away but to be improved upon," he said.
</P>
<P>
In pledging his commitment to upgrading the hotel, Alfred
Ireland, Deputy General Manager of Midroc, said: "We are here to
stay. Uganda is the second country we are investing in Africa
and we hope we sustain the relationship with the government and
the business community."
</P>
<P>
Apollo Hotel Corporation owns the Sheraton Kampala Hotel, one
of the largest and best hotels in Kampala, serving as the
frequent seat for holding big regional and domestic events.
</P>
<P>
The pace of Uganda's privatization program is impressive. By
October 1997, 54 parastatals had been divested in order to meet
the target, set by President Yoweri Museveni in January 1995, of
privatizing 85 percent of parastatals by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country's acute need for financial resources to
rehabilitate the economy, coupled with its heavy indebtedness to
the World Bank and other international financial institutions,
made it necessary to restructure the parastatal sector.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's gross domestic product (GDP) was about 6 billion U.S.
Dollars in 1997 while its external debt stood at more than 3.5
billion U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
