<HEADLINE> Uganda Gives Nod to Third Internet Provider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Investment Authority has
licensed another internet service provider ACR, bringing to three
the number of full internet providers in the country.
</P>
<P>
ACR was granted the license to provide among other services,
e-mail and internet, the New Vision newspaper Wednesday quoted
UIA Investment Officer Dr. James Mutende as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cliff Obi, one of the ACR directors, said that his company is
not only setting its eyes on providing internet services, but
also aims at being a third network operator.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to be the premium internet service provider in
Uganda, providing real-time internet web-browsing capabilities
and e-mail," he said, adding "Our primary goal is to take the
information superhighway to the rural areas, the villages and the
schools."
</P>
<P>
He also said that his company would introduce wireless
communication and use solar energy to power their systems.
</P>
<P>
ACR is a consortium formed by Californian businessmen who
visited the east African country recently. They also plan to
establish video-conferencing and video-phone services. 
</P>
