<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Coastline Threatened: Article </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's 720-kilometer-long
coastline is threatened with inundation, intrusion of salinity and
increased frequency of cyclones, hurricanes, unusual tidal bores
and erosion, a signed article carried by The Daily Star said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Coastal erosion is a major hazard, with which people live along
the coast have had to learn to live, the article said.
</P>
<P>
The coastal eco-system of the country consists of complex delta
of the Ganges-Brahmaputra-Meghna river systems which carry an
estimated annual sediment load of 1.5-1.8 billion tons while
flowing through Bangladesh on their way to Bay of Bengal.
</P>
<P>
The sediment is subjected to coastal dynamic processes
generated mainly by river flow, tide and wind actions, leading to
accretion and erosion in the coastal area.
</P>
<P>
It is said that every year at least a million people are
displaced, and many of them join the ranks of the floating
population and most eventually drift to nearby towns or industrial
belts or end up in Dhaka in search of food, shelter and
employment, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Erosion and accretion are a continuous process along the
coastal belt, and studies show that prominent erosion occurs along
the wide river channels. Most of the erosion of the Bay front was
due to storm surges and wave action.
</P>
<P>
An overall seaward extension of the delta was observed, it
noted, adding on some inhabited islands, erosion is taking place
at an alarming rate. For instance, the area of Sandwip island was
1,080 square km in 1780, but now it has reduced only to 238 square
km.
</P>
<P>
Besides, a sea-level rise by one meter will inundate 17.5
percent of Bangladesh's land, it warned.
</P>
<P>
The article called on the people living along the coast to
enhance their environmental awareness of protecting the coast.
</P>
<P>
The Forest Department of the country has realized the
importance of coastal afforestation as a means for stable
formation. The department has undertaken extensive afforestation
projects in the coastal zone, it stated.
</P>
<P>
It added that the Ministry of Environment and Forest has
already started a multi-million-dollar coastal green-belt project
after the devastating cyclone and tidal surge of April 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Banks Invest Heavily in Housing Sector (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The China Agricultural Bank
announced this week that it will channel 20 billion yuan into the
real estate sector this year, of which 10 billion yuan will be
used for individual mortgages.
</P>
<P>
The China Construction Bank has also released its plan of
offering 25 billion yuan in housing loans this year. So far, all
of China's commercial banks have designed their plans for housing
loans, with an aggregate of more than 100 billion yuan, an
increase of 72 billion yuan over last year.
</P>
<P>
To reach its target of eight percent economic growth this year,
the Chinese government has listed the housing sector as a new area
of economic growth. A new round of fundamental housing reforms
will put a full stop to the welfare housing distribution system
that has been working in China for dozens of years.
</P>
<P>
Starting this year, urban residents will no longer enjoy
low-rent public housing. Instead, they will have to buy houses in
the market with subsidies from their work units.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts believe this is the right time to initiate
the housing reform plan, which will both help solve the housing
difficulties of urban residents and also revitalize the national
economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the present average income level of China's urban
residents is still fairly low. Many people cannot afford to buy a
house on their own, so bank loans become a critical factor for the
success of housing reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Banks Invest Heavily in Housing Sector (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Reliable analysis indicates that investment in residential
housing can give a considerable push to the economy. An input of
10 billion yuan in housing construction can generate social
demands of 17-to-22 billion yuan; while a housing sales volume of
10 billion yuan can spur a consumption of 13-to-15 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts believe that, if the scheduled housing
investment is fully realized, it can contribute 1.8 percent to
this year's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China's commercial banks began offering housing loans in the
early 1990s; now residential housing finance has become the
backbone of housing reform.
</P>
<P>
In line with related policies, the People's Bank of China
(PBOC) issued a circular last week demanding all commercial banks
to channel no less than 15 percent of their newly increased loans
to residential housing.
</P>
<P>
Institutions allowed to accept deposits and offer credit in the
housing sector have been expanded to include all state-owned
commercial banks and the Bank of Communications.
</P>
<P>
The PBOC also demanded that commercial banks give more support
to residential housing consumption.
</P>
<P>
The business climate index for real estate, released this week
by the State Statistics Bureau, shows that increased investment in
the housing sector has been initially successful, with the first
quarter's index obviously recovering from the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts urged financial institutions to further improve related
services, expand the scope of housing finance and make innovations
in housing monetary tools.
</P>
<P>
The central bank should also step up its supervision over
housing loans to avoid possible risks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
