<HEADLINE> Melbourne Workers Protest Against Industrial Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Up to 100,000 people crammed the
center of Melbourne, Australia, Wednesday protesting against the
federal government's industrial laws.
</P>
<P>
The rally was called by the Victorian Trades Hall Council
(VTHC) to protest against the federal government's Workplace
Relations Act, but later it became a massive show of solidarity
with 1,400 dock workers, who are now preparing to resume work
after the High Court decided Monday to reinstate the workers
sacked on April 7.
</P>
<P>
Australian Council of Trade Unions (ACTU) president Jennie
George said the large turnout was the beginning of a community
campaign which would see the federal government thrown out of
office, the Australian Associated Press reported from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
"This day will go down in a very rich history of working class
tradition," she told the protesting workers, "What happened on
Monday in the High Court was a great moral victory, but we haven't
won yet."
</P>
<P>
"This has not been a dispute about productivity. This is has
been a challenge to workers' wages and conditions, this has been a
challenge to workers' rights," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
