<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hotel Occupancy in Vietnam Drops to 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Hotel occupancy in Ho Chi Minh city
and Hanoi dropped to 20 percent in the first quarter of this year,
Vietnam News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, the rate a year ago was 40 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a survey conducted by the Vietnam National
Administration of Tourism (VNAT) as saying that most hotels in the
two cities have seen their occupancy rates decline by 50 to 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
Many hotels have reduced their staff by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Some property development projects under construction have also
been stopped because foreign investors halted capital
contributions to the projects, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
In southern provinces, nine out of 24 inoperative projects have
foreign partners from countries heavily hit by the Asian financial
crisis. The rest, owned by European investors, have been
indirectly affected by the economic woes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
