<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Officials Stand Trial for Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's provincial officials have
been brought to trial for smuggling goods from Cambodia, which
caused an alleged import tax lost of more than 66 billion dong
(about 6.5 million U.S. dollars) within six months, Vietnam News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A local court Tuesday began hearing evidence in the trial of
the 15 defendants, including a former deputy chairman of a
provincial people's committee.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is scheduled to last at least six days.
</P>
<P>
The provincial police and customs officers uncovered the first
smuggling case in January 1996 during a joint inspection of a
shipment of goods from Cambodia which was worth 3.2 billion dong
(about 315,200 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The smugglers were caught red-handed, prompting officers to
launch a series of subsequent investigations, which eventually
uncovered the evidence of anther 171 shipments illegally made over
the previous five months, said the report.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the province's total import tax revenue between
August and December in 1995 was only 3.49 billion dong (about
343,800 dollars), less than five percent of the 70.33 billion dong
(about 6.93 million dollars) expected by the customs authorities,
said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
