<HEADLINE> Zambian Football Association Dissolved over Fund Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of Zambia
(FAZ) has been dissovled by the country's Sports Council (SCZ)
over alleged abuse of funds, Times of Zambia reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dicision was announced Tuesday in Ndola, 330 kilometers
north of the capital, by Lloyd Siame, chairman of SCZ's legal and
disciplinary sub-committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
The matter has been handed over to police and SCZ has furnished
FIFA, the world soccer governing body with reasons for their
action.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Siame as saying that the dicision to dissove
FAZ follows a audit report on the funding given to FAZ to prepare
the national team for the 1998 African Nations Cup (ANC) held last
February in Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
Siame further revealed that the FAZ constitution has also been
suspended and an interim committee will be put in place soon.
</P>
<P>
The SCZ's legal and disciplinary sub-committee has been
investigating FAZ on 2.8 billion Kwacha (about 2 million
U.S. dollars) given by the Zambian government for the Birkina Faso
tournament.
</P>
<P>
However, the investigations showed that 577 million Kwacha
(400,000 dollars) was not accounted for, while a further 212
million Kwacha (140,000 dollars) was spent on items unrelated to
the preparations for the tournament in which the Zambian team
performed disappointedly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
