<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Bars Public Officials from Honorary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has banned
all serving public officials from accepting awards of honorary
degrees, fellowships and other related titles from local or
foreign institutions.
</P>
<P>
The ban, according to Secretary to the Federal Government
Alhaji Gidado Idris, is to check the abuses of such honors, press
reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Government has observed with concern that the time-honored
practice of honoring deserving persons with honorary degrees,
diplomas, fellowships, etc., is being abused," he said in a
circular dated April 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
According to him, "the situation has deteriorated to the
extent that the established procedures for bestowing such honors
are no longer observed."
</P>
<P>
"In some cases, the intentions for giving the award appear
less than noble. It is hardly surprising that these awards no
longer command much respect."
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, serving public officials are barred from
accepting honorary degrees, fellowships, etc. from domestic or
foreign universities, polytechnics and other higher institutions.
</P>
<P>
The ban, however, does not apply to fellowships and
memberships awarded by accredited professional bodies to their
bonafide members, said the circular which was copied to key
government functionaries.
</P>
<P>
The government in September 1997 clamped a similar ban on the
acceptance of chieftaincy or traditional titles by sitting
ministers and other public officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
