<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 70 Percent of Zambian Adults Infected with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 70 percent of Zambian adults
have been infected with tuberculosis and nearly one in very 200
Zambians get the disease every year, according to press releases
reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Tuberculosis and Leprosy Trust (ZATULET) said in the
releases that Zambia is one of the countries in southern Africa
with the highest number of tuberculosis cases.
</P>
<P>
With a population of only 8,275,000 in 1996, the number of
detected tuberculosis cases per 100,000 stood at 448 while South
Africa with a population of 42,393,000 had a case detection rate
of 216 per 100,000. Uganda had 139 tuberculosis patients per
100,000.
</P>
<P>
At least four out every 10 adults in Zambia dying from medical
problems are due to tuberculosis, said one press release.
</P>
<P>
"Taking into account of the various constraints like the lack
of finance, government's low commitment to the program and the
low socio-economical status of our people, the problem of
tuberculosis will continue to cause havoc on the population of
our nation," ZATULET Executive Director David Mondoka said in a
release.
</P>
<P>
"Tuberculosis poses as one of the most serious health problem
of our times. It is devastating a lot of our people's lives day
in and day out," Mondaka said, adding that "many people,
especially the young of between 15 and 39 years of age are the
most affected age group according to the statistics."
</P>
<P>
ZATULET is a newly-formed non-governmental organization with
its main aim to supplement or complement government's efforts in
case-finding, diagnosing, treating, controlling and preventing
both tuberculosis and leprosy in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist Says Bigger Oil Fields Expected To Be Found in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist said here today
that there is a great possibility that China might find big oil
fields in coming years.
</P>
<P>
Li Guangding, an academician from the Geophysics Institute of
the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: "From east China to the
southern Beibu Gulf, there exist some 40 basins which were on the
bottom of ancient oceans and may contain abundant oil and gas."
</P>
<P>
He said that some of the potential oil fields are expected to
be larger than any of those currently in operation.
</P>
<P>
Liu announced his findings at an international symposium on
modern physics held at Beijing University. He said that previous
drilling was done mainly in continental basins where oil was
formed in rivers and lakes in the Cenozoic Era.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 million years ago, the piece of land where China is
now located was under an ocean. After the sea receded and the
continent began to emerge 200 million years ago, basins containing
oil were left.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Liu, drastic mountain-making movements
occurred afterward which distorted the shapes of the basins, and
made it difficult for scientists to find them.
</P>
<P>
"China's geological history features extreme complexity. There
have been theoretical and technological problems in our work," he
said.
</P>
<P>
But breakthroughs have been made recently, according to the
scientist. A well was drilled last year in northeast China from an
ocean-formed basin which turned out 1,000 tons of oil a day.
</P>
<P>
"More advanced geophysic methods should be applied in
researching basins left over from pre-Cenozoic time, where we have
done little work," he said.
</P>
<P>
China produced 143 million tons of land oil and 16.2 million
tons of offshore oil last year.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of China's economy has greatly increased
oil demands. Statistics show that China imported 33.8 million
crude and refined oil last year, up 140 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
China has signed contracts with several countries to jointly
drill for oil in the Middle East and South America.
</P>
<P>
However, many experts said that in the coming 10 years, China
should mainly supply itself with domestic oil products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0210 </DOCNO>
