<HEADLINE> 20,000 Ugandans Flee Homes in West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 20,000 Ugandans have fled
their homes in the west in the wake of the government troops'
operations against the rebels there.
</P>
<P>
The authorities have registered 10,000 refugees in Bundibugyo
District and need urgent food supplies to support them, the New
Vision newspaper Wednesday quoted Edward Masiga, the resident
district commissioner, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The paper estimated that the number of the Ugandans fleeing
their homes might amount to 20,000.
</P>
<P>
Francis Onyai, Chief Administrative Official of the district,
confirmed that many people have fled their homes and taken refuge
in towns in the district.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government troops launched operations in recent
days against the rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) in
the district and inflicted casualties on the ADF rebels. And the
local residents feared the revenge from the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program had started distributing food to the
refugees, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Allied Democratic Forces are a rebel group active in the
west with hundreds remnants based in Rwenzori in western
districts of Kasese and Bundibugyo.
</P>
<P>
The ADF remnants earlier fled their camps in the east of the
Democratic Republic of Congo since the joint operation against
them launched by government troops of Uganda and Democratic
Congo.
</P>
<P>
Previously, ADF had some 1,500 fighters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
