<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Comptroller's Report Ignites Religious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The report of Israeli State
Comptroller criticizing the preferential treatment given to the
ultra-Orthodox segments of society, has ignited a storm of
protests by religious parties.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz said on Wednesday that most of the
religious leaders lashed out at the state comptroller Miriam
Ben-Porat, calling her report a "gimmick" and "disgrace".
</P>
<P>
Ben-Porat in her report issued Tuesday, noted that benefits
were given to religious and ultra-Orthodox settlements even though
they were ineligible according to the government's national
priority map, and lands were allocated to the ultra-Orthodox
without legally tenders.
</P>
<P>
The report devoted several chapters to the millions of shekels
allocated to the religious and ultra-Orthodox sectors in defiance
of official criteria for these allocations.
</P>
<P>
The primary theme of Ben-Porat report drove straight to the
heart of one of Israel's most fundamental divides, the struggle
for power between secular and ultra-Orthodox segments of society.
</P>
<P>
"Power tends to corrupt. You need great self-control to resist
temptations when power is in your hands," Ben-Porat said in the
48th annual State Comptroller's report, covering 1997.
</P>
<P>
In response, Deputy Religious Affairs Minister, Rabbi Arieh
Camliel, said Ben-Porat "had exceeded her charge and is talking
like a politician. " He said Ben Porat was using the
ultra-Orthodox public as a gimmick to draw attention to her
report.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Housing Minister Meir Porush, of the ultra-Orthodox
United Torah Judaism Party, accused by Ben-Porat of favoring his
constituents in housing projects, also said the report "fits in
well with the general onslaught against ultra-Orthodox Judaism."
</P>
<P>
Porush said he had never encountered "such an ugly and
disgraceful campaign of calumny" as the one currently being waged
against the ultra-Orthodox population.
</P>
<P>
Since Likud coalition came to power in 1996, the religious
power has been growing in the country. And in the 120-seat
Knesset (parliament), there are 23 ultra-Orthodox members, who
play an important role in formulating policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
