<HEADLINE> Election-Related Violence Drops in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Chairman Bernardo Pardo of the
Philippine Commission on Elections said Wednesday that there was a
decrease in election-related violence with only five days to go
before the May 11 elections.
</P>
<P>
Citing statistics, Pardo said only 58 election-related
incidents were reported as of Wednesday, compared to 194 in the
1992 national polls and 121 in the 1995 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
The number of persons killed in election-related violence also
fell to only 27, compared to 83 and 56 during the two previous
elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pardo cited these figures at a press briefing held during a
break of a command conference attended by the chief of the
national police, deputy chief of staff of the armed forces and
other senior officials of the Department of Interior and Local
Government and the Commission on Elections.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, Philippine National Police chief
Santiago Alino said the national police would declare a red alert
two days before the May 11 elections.
</P>
<P>
He said 70 percent of the police forces will also be deployed
to help the military ensure peaceful elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
