<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Tumble in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo
Wednesday with the key Nikkei index closing at its lowest level
since January 14, on renewed concerns about credit risks in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plummeted 357.26 points or
2.29 percent from last Friday's close to 15,243.84. The Tokyo
market was closed Monday and Tuesday for national holidays.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 17.04 points or 1.40 percent to
1,200.66.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section went up to an estimated 350
million shares from Friday's 300 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Wednesday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Stocks were sold in Tokyo and other Asian markets on
speculation that Tuesday's riots in Indonesia over the planned
fuel and electricity price hikes could rekindle the Asian economic
crisis, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Comments overnight in Washington by Koichi Kato, secretary
general of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party, also affected
the Tokyo market, they said.
</P>
<P>
Kato said Tuesday that more bankruptcies of major financial
institutions may occur in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,329 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outpaced gainers 866 to 295, with 134 remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
