<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Brings Hope to Poor County </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Zhangxian County, formerly one of
the poorest counties in China, has been transformed into a booming
tourism attraction.
</P>
<P>
The county town in northwest China's Gansu Province features
impressive hotels, karaoke clubs, coffee houses and boutiques
lining what were previously desolate streets.
</P>
<P>
Polite young men and women dressed in colorful clothing greet
tourists in standard Chinese. Ironically, a few years ago girls
never dared wear skirts and dirty-faced young men avoided
strangers.
</P>
<P>
Tourists are flocking to Dingxi Prefecture to view the county's
over 3,700 canyons filled with spectacular mountains, scenic
rivers, waterfalls and historic sites.
</P>
<P>
The 1992 nationwide boom in tourism encouraged local Zhangxian
officials to introduce tourism in order to eradicate poverty. The
prefecture has since hosted over 1.4 million tourists, with total
earning from tourism surpassing 25 million yuan (three million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Although Tourism revenues account for only a small proportion
of the local economy, the sector offers highly beneficial social
effects, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
While 78 percent of the local population lived below the
poverty line in the early 1980s, the proportion has declined
dramatically to only 18 percent at present.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
