<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Manufacturers to Earn 100 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambian manufacturers will earn 100
million U.S. Dollars from their exports to South Africa once the
two governments sign and ratify a non-reciprocal trade agreement
this month.
</P>
<P>
"This is a major achievement for Zambia and local exporters
will now be earning a total of 100 million dollars from their
exports to South Africa alone," Mark O'Donnell, Chairman of the
Zambia Association of Manufacturers, said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Wednesday quoted O'Donnell as saying
that when Zambia signs the long-awaited non-reciprocal agreement
with South Africa, local exporters will thereafter export their
goods freely to South Africa and other member countries of the
Southern African Custom Union (SACU).
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Zambian manufacturers will export their
goods to South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Swaziland and Lesotho
at reduced duties unlike now when they find it difficult to
export goods to SACU member countries because of high duties, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Zambian manufacturers earn less than 50 million
U.S. Dollars from their exports to South Africa because of stiff
trade barriers imposed by the SACU member countries, according to
the chairman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
