<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cashmere Price Drops in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The purchasing price for cashmere
in Mongolia has dropped in the past few days by 12.8 percent to
10,000 togrog (about 12.2 U.S. dollars) one kilogram.
</P>
<P>
In some places, the price has been as low as 9,000 togrog
(about 11 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The price was 11,500 togrog (about 14 dollars) a kilogram a
month ago when the new marketing season just began, news reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The drop was mainly due to higher export duties imposed by the
government last year to limit export.
</P>
<P>
As a result, exporters have to lower their purchasing prices to
make a profit.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia, the second largest cashmere exporter in the world,
has a 25 percent share of the international market. The country is
expected to produce more than 3,000 tons this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Use Bank Loans To Become Prosperous (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- When Goinjue Cering borrowed 6,000
yuan from the bank in the early 1980s, villagers all believed that
he must have gone crazy as all his personal belongings could not
pay back the loan.
</P>
<P>
To date, nobody in the village has a similar reaction if
someone plans to borrow from the bank because Goinjue has become a
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
To Tibetans, bank loans used to be considered more horrible
than ghosts and as a last resort in extreme poverty. Until the
1980s banks in the suburbs of Lhasa, capital of the Tibet
Autonomous Region, found it very difficult to find prospective
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
And, among the limited amounts of bank loans, more than 70
percent of them were used for daily necessities instead of
business transactions.
</P>
<P>
With the implementation of a series of aid-the-poor projects
and the renouncement of Tibetans' outdated concepts, a growing
number of Tibetans have become prosperous by borrowing to set up
their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
Danzim, a farmer in Qiumu village of Namling County, borrowed
5,000 yuan from the bank to start his own flour mill three years
ago. The mill now brings 20,000 yuan of annual income for his
family.
</P>
<P>
Dawa Cering and Zhaxi Jangyang, two brothers in Gurong Village
of Doilungdeqen County, borrowed 110,000 yuan from the bank in
1993. They used the loan to set up their own business producing a
sort of glutinous rice cake that is used to supply to the Potala
Palace.
</P>
<P>
The glutinous rice cakes not only sell well in China, but have
now entered the markets of India and Nepal, earning the brothers
more than 200,000 yuan of net income last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
