<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Use Bank Loans To Become Prosperous (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two brothers have paid back their loans, purchased flats in
Lhasa, and bought a brand-now Dongfeng Brand truck.
</P>
<P>
"The changes are really great," sighed president of the
Agriculture Bank in Doilungdeqen County.
</P>
<P>
"I used to travel to every corner of the county to look for
potential borrowers and often ended in vain, " he said.
</P>
<P>
"Nowadays, I just sit in my office, and wait for the farmers
who come to me one after another and, more importantly, they
borrow funds to start a business instead of to purchase daily
necessities."
</P>
<P>
As the Tibetan farmers and herdsmen develop a deeper
understanding of loans, the total amount borrowed by Tibetans has
been on the rise for several years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the farmers and herdsmen of the
autonomous region had borrowed 427 million yuan in 1997, which
means that the amount of loan for each person is higher than the
national average.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the average bank deposit of Tibet's farmers and
herdsmen has climbed to 184 yuan, double the figure in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
"We have the obligation to deposit our surplus money into the
bank, which will help more people out of poverty," said Cering
Bandian of Nedong County in Shannan Prefecture, "as we are the
direct beneficiaries of the bank loans."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0235 </DOCNO>
