<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Industrial Sector Tackles Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The industrial sector of Shanghai,
the biggest city in China, has made progress in reducing
pollutants while maintaining sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The city has closed or relocated more than 1,000 polluting
enterprises in its urban areas in the past decade, eliminating
300 polluting sources and clearing an urban ground space
of 3.75 million square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The city's industrial structure has also become more rational
through reducing the ratio of seriously polluting industries and
developing high-tech ones. The city has formed six pillar
industries headed by auto manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
About 30 billion yuan (3.7 billion U.S. dollars) has been spent
annually on renovating industrial technology and pollution
control, which resulted in a sharp decrease of discharged
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
The discharge of waste water per 100 million yuan of industrial
output valaue has been reduced from 485,000 tons to 178,000 tons;
waste gas, from 172 million cubic meters to 92 million cubic
meters; and solid waste, from 51,000 tons to 24,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The city has also invested two billion yuan annually in recent
years in treating old polluting enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
