<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 07:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Denies Arafat's Remarks on Abu Dis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) has denied a report that President Yasser Arafat had
accepted Abu Dis on Jerusalem's suburb as capital of the future
Palestinian state, the Hebrew-language Haaretz daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its front-page story Tuesday, Haaretz reported that Arafat
told a delegation from the New York-based Council of Foreign
Relations that the 1996 Beilin-Abu Mazen and Beilin-Eitan
agreements were realistic foundations for a final settlement with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Asked if an agreement could be reached on the sensitive issue
of Jerusalem, Arafat was quoted as replying: "Certainly, the idea
of Abu Dis, which belonged to Al Quds (Jerusalem) under Jordanian
control, is acceptable."
</P>
<P>
But PNA Cabinet Secretary Ahmed Abdel Rahman said the report
was untrue. He said that Arafat told the delegation that East
Jerusalem is occupied territory and an integral part of the rest
of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Council has resolved that Jerusalem
will be the capital of an independent Palestinian state and the
United Nations Resolution 242 calling for Israeli pullout from
occupied territories also refers to East Jerusalem, Rahman said.
</P>
<P>
However, Haaretz repeated that one of participants in the
meeting said on condition of anonymity that Arafat had in fact
spoken about setting up the Palestinian capital in Abu Dis.
</P>
<P>
Henry Siegman, head of the American delegation, told the
English-language daily The Jerusalem Post that Arafat said "there
are several plans for the resolution of the problem of Jerusalem
that can serve as an acceptable basis for discussion."
</P>
<P>
He even confirmed that Arafat singled out the Beilin-Abu Mazen
plan as one such promising proposal and indicated that the idea of
Abu Dis serve as a Palestinian capital is one of several worth of
consideration.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that according to the plan formulated by
Israel's Labor lawmaker Yossi Beilin and Arafat's deputy Abu Mazen
in 1996, the future capital of a Palestinian state will be set up
in Abu Dis in East Jerusalem's suburb. Most settlements under
Israeli control will remain, whereas settlers living in highly
populated Palestinian areas could live in the Palestinian state or
move to Israeli territories.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is the most sensitive issue that should be solved in
the final-status talks under the Oslo accords. Israel has vowed
not to relinquish its sovereign control over the whole Jerusalem,
while the Palestinian side hopes to establish a state with East
Jerusalem as the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
