<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fruit Growers Cutting Down Thousands of Bad Quality Date Saplings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Fruit growers in the city of Leling
in east China's Shandong Province had destroyed 200,000 Chinese
date saplings by the end of March because they were no good.
</P>
<P>
The small Chinese date, or jujube, has sold well for years,
even when sales of other jujubes were down, with a kilogram of
small Chinese dates going for more than 10 yuan (1.2 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In Leling, the hometown of jujubes, the trees are referred to
as "money trees" by farmers, and since 1995, it has been common
for a farmer here to earn 30,000-40,000 yuan a year from the fruit.
</P>
<P>
But, during a planting spree, some farmers paid less attention
to the quality of saplings than to the price and ended up eating
the bad fruit they had planted themselves after one bad harvest
last year.
</P>
<P>
Hu Panhe, a farmer of the village of Zhangtiechui, was quoted
by People's Daily as saying that the jujubes from his 25 bad
saplings last year were still in piles even though the price had
dropped to 3 yuan per kg. And not a single one of his "money
trees" dropped any money on him.
</P>
<P>
The recent inferior sapling cutting campaign was organized by
the city government. The local sapling growers association is
supporting the move by providing a better strain of saplings to
farmers at 80 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts explain that better saplings are the only way
to avoid stagnant fruit sales, because quality is more important
than quantity on today's agricultural produce market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
