<HEADLINE> Tourism Blooms in Northwest China's Autonomous Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Northwestern China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region is expected to receive 200,000 overseas tourists
and six million domestic tourists this year.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Xinjiang had an annual increase of 69 percent in the
number of overseas tourists, much higher than the country's
average of 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
Abul'ahat Abdurixit, chairman of Xinjiang, said the regional
government now plans to attract more tourists to this region,
which occupies one-sixth of China's total area.
</P>
<P>
Besides pillar industries such as petroleum and cotton, he
said, tourism is expected to become a new economic growth area for
the region.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1978, tourism earned 46,000 U.S. dollars of foreign
currency for Xinjiang. Overseas tourists spent over 70 million
U.S. dollars in Xinjiang in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said he was confident in the region's tourism
potential, which comes from the abundant resources and steady
development of infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
Situated in the middle of the "Silk Road," Xinjiang used to be
an important area for economic and cultural exchanges between the
West and the East.
</P>
<P>
To develop tourism, Xinjiang extended telephone lines from
urban to rural areas, and constructed a high-rated road connecting
the tourism cities of Urumqi and Turpan, which will be in
operation before August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
