<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eastern China's Province Develops Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, May 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has made
great efforts to strengthen infrastructure construction and
improve investment environment in recent years.
</P>
<P>
An official from the provincial government said that, in the
1979-1997 period, Fujian province completed 425 billion yuan of
fixed assets investment, with 118 billion yuan in infrastructure
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The 1992-1997 period was the prime period for infrastructure
construction in Fujian, with investment of 79.1 billion yuan,
accounting for 55 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Fujian Province constructed and reconstructed a series of major
projects for water supply, electricity, railways and
airports. After years of effort, the province has had rapid
increases in transportation and handling capacity of ports.
</P>
<P>
The province has four civil airports including the two
international airports of Xiamen Changqi and Fuzhou Changle.
</P>
<P>
The first expressway in Fujian (Quanzhou-Xiamen) was in
operation in December of 1997, followed by the Xiamen-Zhangzhou
expressway. The Fuzhou-Quanzhou expressway is under construction.
</P>
<P>
With the operation of several large thermal power plants and
hydro-power plants, Fujian Province is no longer short of
electricity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Looking At New Railway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China is considering building a new
railway as part of an east-west artery in the southern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary work on the railway, from Longyan in Fujian
Province to Ganzhou in Jiangxi Province and to Shaoguan in
Guangdong Province is now underway.
</P>
<P>
The 488-km railway would link up with the Yingtan-Xiamen
railway and Nanning-Kunming railway, cutting the distance from
coastal parts of Fujian to southern and central China by some 344
km.
</P>
<P>
The railway department had, in fact, already included the
project on its construction scheme as early as the 1950s, but a
lack of funds put a halt to construction.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that more than two million people who live along
the proposed route will benefit from the projected railway.
</P>
</TEXT>
