<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government to Assist Poor Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government will
provide special scholarships to more than 400,000 cash-strapped
university students nationwide to help them continue their
studies, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
The National Development Planning Board will provide at least
200 billion rupiah (25 million U.S. dollars) to help students
whose parents have been severely affected by the national economic
turmoil, Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry
Ginandjar Kartasasmita said here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Sixty percent of the scholarships will be extended to students
majoring in science and mathematics and the rest to those majoring
in social sciences, with priority to be given to female students,
the official Antara News Agency Wednesday quoted the minister as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare Haryono
Suyono said some 9,000 of the students who will get scholarships
come from families whose monthly income is less than 250,000
rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 8,000 rupiah).
</P>
<P>
He said the government will also provide scholarships to 1.2
million elementary and junior and senior high school students
through the Foster Parent Program.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar meanwhile denied that the scholarships are aimed at
making students quit a protest against the government which has
been going on since January this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
