<HEADLINE> Australian Swimmer Suspended for Three Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- World championship silver medalist
Richard Upton of Australia has received a three-month suspension
for a positive test to a banned substance.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Arbitration for Sport found that Upton breached
Australian Olympic Committee rules in returning a positive test to
probenecid.
</P>
<P>
Australian Swimming had earlier decided against banning Upton,
accepting his evidence that he was prescribed the drug by his
family doctor to fight a throat infection.
</P>
<P>
The CAS ban was backdated to February 17, the day of the
out-of-competition test. Upton took the substance following a
visit to his doctor on February 14.
</P>
<P>
Upton won a medal as a relay swimmer at the Perth world
championships in January. He failed last week to make Australia's
team for the Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur in September.
</P>
