<HEADLINE> China's Township Firms Getting More Funds For Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 6 (Xinhua) -- A hundred million yuan for technical
improvements is expected to help the Luli Group Co., a plywood
manufacturer in the city of Shouguang in east China's Shandong
Province, to become a major power in that business.
</P>
<P>
The company can now produce 1.2 billion cu.m. of plywood a year.
</P>
<P>
Shandong is the home of the second most powerful group of
township level enterprises in the country, with total asset valued
at 160 billion yuan. But, their products have not been very
competitive because of the backwardness of the production
facilities and the lack of technology.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the provincial government has said that technical
improvements in township firms should come before new factories,
and since that time, 40 million yuan has been allocated annually
for technology to get the firms to compete with state enterprises
on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 20 billion yuan was spent on 9,600 technical
improvement projects, which are expected to generate 70 billion
yuan worth of goods and 9.5 billion yuan in pre-tax profits.
</P>
<P>
Investment priority has been given to the machinery, chemical,
and building industries, and 36 key improvement projects have used
1.05 billion yuan since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of HIV/AIDS Patients in China Continues to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China had 9,970 people infected with
the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) on record at the end of
March, 290 of which had fully developed acquired immune deficiency
syndrome (AIDS) and 173 others had died.
</P>
<P>
The official figures, released by the Ministry of Health
(MOH) on Tuesday, represent a small rise from the figures for
last October, when there were 8,303 HIV carriers.
</P>
<P>
AIDS experts have estimated that between 200,000 and 250,000
Chinese were in fact infected by the virus at the end of 1997,
compared with 150,000 to 200,000 in 1996. They have warned that
any failure to act promptly could result in an increase to one
million by early next century.
</P>
<P>
Intravenous drug use remains the leading cause of HIV
infections in China, with other cases resulting from sexual
activities and contaminated blood. There are also instances of
infants being infected, the MOH reports.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in the number of HIV cases related to intravenous
drug use and sexual contacts indicates a critical HIV epidemic in
China," said Sun Longchun, vice-minister of the MOH.
</P>
<P>
He told an awards giving ceremony for an essay contest on "AIDS
and Adolescents" in Beijing that China needs a larger publicity
campaign to provide information about HIV/AIDS for the Chinese,
especially youngsters. The Ministry of Education has got some 600
essays and posters on the subject from middle school students and
their teachers from across China in the past four months.
</P>
<P>
"We've learned from the participants' works that a great number of
youngsters still know little about HIV/AIDS. Promoting health
awareness among them is an urgent matter," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Ten percent of those Chinese infected with the HIV is under the
age of 19, and most of them are victims of intravenous drug use.
</P>
<P>
According to a national questionnaire in 1997, 60 percent of
adolescents in China knew nothing about the basic knowledge of
HIV/AIDS, and 21 percent about HIV/AIDS prevention.
</P>
<P>
The awards giving ceremony was attended by Peng Peiyun,
vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, and Dr. Peter Piot, Executive Director of the Joint
United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS, who is in China on
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Encouraging Non-state Enterprise Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The non-state economic sector in
China is getting stronger support from the central government as
it plays an increasingly important role in economic growth and
employment.
</P>
<P>
When President Jiang Zemin's recent visit to township
enterprises in the eastern province of Jiangsu signalled greater
government support for the sector, the People's Bank, China's
central bank, announced that financial institutions would increase
credit for medium-sized and small businesses.
</P>
<P>
The sector includes township enterprises, private businesses,
urban collective enterprises, and cooperative companies that issue
stock and have no state capital. Of these, the private sector
alone contributes 30 percent to the total industrial output and
employs more than 13 million workers.
</P>
<P>
By now, two decades of reforms and development have put the
sector in a position where it matches the state-owned economy, and
the central government is encouraging private and township
enterprises to buy into small and medium-sized state firms.
</P>
<P>
Some provinces are going even further than this. Shandong
Province in east China, for example, has adopted some policies
that allow government functionaries to develop private
businesses. And Henan and Shaanxi provinces are also poised to
change the ownership of small and medium-sized state businesses,
while trying to protect their interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Offered 43m Dlrs for Upgrading Seaports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has
offered a 43-million-U.S.-dollar package investment for upgrading
Bangladesh's two seaports, the independent Associated Press of
Bangladesh (APB) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ADB set a precondition for the funds that all operational
sides inside jetties and outer anchorage be privatized to reap
maximum benefit from the parts, ADB officials were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The ADB-appointed Mott Macdonal Ltd. and Associates had
prepared a report on "Bangladesh Port Upgrading Project" and
completed a draft final report which had been handed over to
Chittagong Port Authority (CPA) a few days ago, APB noted.
</P>
<P>
A preliminary economic analysis has been carried out and a
detailed economic and financial analysis will be soon submitted
with the final report.
</P>
<P>
The donor stressed full privatization of port operations such
as container handling, onshore and offshore activities for greater
productivity, breaking the chain of persisting irregularities
which nearly crippled the port, the report said, adding the CPA
expressed its soft reaction and reservation to the issue as it was
considered most sensational by trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Such steps might trigger major labor unrest and even cause
collapse of port activity, CPA officials warned, adding partial
privatization in some sectors excepting existing function by CPA
could be allowed and reasonable if the government agreed to in
principle.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's major seaport of Chittagong had been facing
serious problems like equipment and space shortage, APB pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, trade unions active in Chittagong Port
strongly oppose any privatization attempt, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
