<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Parliament Passes Bills on CHT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi parliament has passed
three bills on the country's southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts
(CHT), which are reportedly aimed at giving legal effect to a
peace accord between the government and hill tribals.
</P>
<P>
The Bandarban Hill District Local Government Council
(Amendment) Bill was passed by the Jatiya Sangsad on Tuesday
night, despite strong opposition from the opposition Jatiya Party
and absence of MPs from the major opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The parliament passed two similar bills on Sunday and Monday
respectively on Rangamati and Khagrachhari, the other two
districts of the hill tracts, which account for nearly 10 percent
of the country's total area of about 148,000 square kilometers and
less than 1 percent of its population of about 127 million.
</P>
<P>
The opposition have fiercely attacked the treaty since it was
signed last December, accusing the treaty of "violating" the
country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was designed to end the decades-long armed conflict
in the hill tracts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
