<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Customs Returns Ancient Chinese Artifacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Customs Tuesday returned
some four dozen Chinese antiquities to China in compliance with a
relevant U.N. convention.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held at the Chinese Embassy at which 47
artifacts seized by the U.S. Customs Service in Tampa last July
were brought back to their rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
The antiquities are believed to date back to the Han, Tang and
Ming Dynasties covering the years from 206 B.C. to 1644 A.D. U.S.
experts in this field estimate that they have a wholesale of about
23,000 U.S. dollars, but their market prices are said to be over
10,000 dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The artifacts, ceramic articles removed from Chinese burial
sites, were presented to Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing by Acting
Customs Commissioner Sam Banks at a spacious hall where 27 of the
returned pieces were put on display.
</P>
<P>
When Banks handed over the relevant documents to Ambassador Li,
officials from both sides gave applause to endorse the cooperation
in preventing smuggling Chinese cultural property to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The artifacts were seized when a Customs inspector, suspicious
of goods labeled as Chinese antiquities, examined the shipment and
discovered 47 antiquities, all without the requisite Chinese
licenses for the legal export of cultural artifacts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Customs authority informed the Chinese Embassy of the
seizure, and arrangements were made for the return of the
artifacts.
</P>
<P>
Sources from both sides confirmed that it was the first time
the U.S. Customs returned antiquities to China, but it was not the
first time the U.S. Customs seized Chinese artifacts in Tampa
and Seattle. Several shipments were turned back to the ports of
departure.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States are signatories to the 1970 UNESCO
Convention on the Means of Prohibiting and Preventing the Illicit
Import, Export and Transfer of Ownership of Cultural Property.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Banks said, "The people of China have
a very rich and very old cultural heritage and Customs is proud to
have played a role in helping to preserve it."
</P>
<P>
The acting commissioner added that customs of the United States
and China enjoy very close cooperation in this field.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Li in his turn expressed deep appreciation to the
U.S. Customs Services in Tampa, Florida, for its prompt seizure of
the Chinese artifacts at the request of the Chinese Embassy and
for its hard work in the technical appraisal of so many pieces of
heavy objects.
</P>
<P>
"I would also like to express the same deep appreciation to the
headquarters of the U.S. Customs Service in Washington, DC, for
its decision to return these precious artifacts to their rightful
owner," Li added.
</P>
<P>
He described the Sino-U.S. cooperation in preventing Chinese
cultural property from being illegally brought into the U.S. as
"gratifying and effective."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador disclosed that partially as a follow-up
to this friendly gesture, the State Bureau of Cultural Relics of
China and the U.S. Embassy in Beijing have started consultations
for a bilateral agreement based on the 1970 UNESCO Convention.
</P>
<P>
"With all these, we have every reason to expect a strengthened
cooperation in the implementation of the UNESCO Convention between
our two countries," Ambassador Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li presented to Banks a miniature copy of an ancient Chinese
bronze cooking vessel called "Ding" in Chinese, which, he said,
"symbolizes not only stability but also friendship." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
