<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Launch Job Creation Schemes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia government is set to
launch the second phase of labor-intensive projects in mid-May at
a cost of 1 trillion rupiah (125 million U.S. dollars) to help
create jobs, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"This program will get under way on May 18 in all provinces,"
Manpower Minister Theo L. Sambuaga said here Tuesday. The first
phase of labor-intensive projects was launched between January and
March this year at a cost of 6.2 billion rupiah (775,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the projects will target both skilled and
unskilled workers who have become unemployed as a result of the
economic crisis and the prolonged drought, local leading
newspapers Wednesday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said 116,000 unskilled workers in rural and urban areas of
215 districts and municipalities will gain daily employment
through a nationwide program of 598 billion rupiah (74.8 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
They will be hired to work in a range of projects, including
the renovation of traditional markets, roadwork and irrigation
development.
</P>
<P>
They will also be placed to work in the fisheries, agriculture
and commerce sectors.
</P>
<P>
For skilled workers laid off from their jobs, the government
has allocated 399 billion rupiah (about 50 million dollars) to
fund the creation of 65,000 job opportunities in 18 provinces, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Skilled workers will be employed as business consultants,
technicians, managers, operations facilitators or administrative
staff at productive business institutions, such as social
cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the number of unemployed people in
Indonesia has reached 9 million and is estimated to increase to 13
million by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been hit by the regional monetary crisis and its
economy is expected to contract by 5 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
