<HEADLINE> Cohen Urges Congress to Repeal Land Mine Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- United States Defense Secretary
William Cohen and U.S. military leaders are urging Congress to
repeal a law on the use of anti-personnel land mines, the Pentagon
said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The law bans U.S. use of land mines for one year, starting from
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and the Joint Chiefs of Staff asked Congress in a letter
to repeal the law which was passed and signed by U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Defense Department spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters that the
U.S. military needed more time to develop alternatives to land
mines.
</P>
<P>
He said the military would have to add thousands of troops and
hundreds of tanks and other weaponry in a potential conflict
situation to make up for any lack of mines.
</P>
<P>
Clinton refused to sign an international agreement against land
mines in Ottawa last year, claiming that the U.S. military needed
"an adequate transition period to seek out alternatives to
anti-personnel land mines," Bacon said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
