<HEADLINE> Bangkok Residents to Hand in Rat Tails for Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangkok residents will be given a
new way to earn money as the city authorities are considering an
economical way to rid the city of rats.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper The Nation reported Wednesday that the Bangkok
metropolitan administration is considering encouraging residents
to catch rats and sell their tails to the local government, which
would save millions of baht to be required for hiring a private
company.
</P>
<P>
The project, if approved, will be implemented as soon as
possible, an adviser to the Bangkok governor said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that apart from the 6 million human residents,
there are 50 million rats living in Bangkok's 1,500 square
kilometers of areas.
</P>
<P>
The figure came from a Hungarian company which conducted a
survey of rats in the Thai capital.
</P>
<P>
The company has proposed to eliminate the rodents at a cost of
about 300 million baht (7.89 million U.S. dollars), the adviser
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the price was considered too high with the country
facing an economic downturn and so the city authorities came up
with the short-term rat tails-for-money project.
</P>
<P>
"This project will be short-term as the problem of rats-borne
disease should be tackled as soon as possible," the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
It would also help jobless people earn money since it would not
be too costly to implement, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
