<HEADLINE> PLA Chief of Staff Stresses China's Defensive Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- China's national defense policy is of
a totally defensive nature with no intent at hegemony, aggression
or expansion, a visiting top Chinese military official said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Fu Quanyou, chief of the general staff of the Chinese People's
Liberation Army (PLA) and member of China's Central Military
Commission, made the remark at a meeting with Inspector-General of
the Austrian Federal Army Karl Majcen.
</P>
<P>
While implementing a strategy of active defense, China does not
seek military alliances with any country. Nor does it station any
troops abroad or establish overseas military bases, said Fu.
</P>
<P>
He said the PLA's mission is to strengthen the national
defense, fend off aggression, safeguard territorial sovereignty
and the rights and interests of territorial waters, and maintain
national integrity and safety.
</P>
<P>
China's national defense and military construction are
subordinate to the country's economic development, with servicemen
supporting and taking an active part in economic construction,
especially in rushing aid and relief to emergencies and
disaster-hit areas, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
On military relations between China and Austria, Fu and Majcen
agreed that the two armed forces should increase multi-level and
multi-area exchange and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Fu arrived in Vienna on Monday for a four-day visit to
Austria. He had talks with Austrian Defense Minister Werner
Fasslabend on his arrival.
</P>
<P>
Austria is the second stop on Fu's four-leg tour which has
already taken him to India. He will next visit the Czech Republic
and Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
