<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Trade Giant Avoids Regional Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 6 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangdong Province, a
major source of foreign trade, managed to avoid the Asian
financial crisis and maintained foreign trade growth in the first
few months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Its imports and exports were worth 29.3 billion US dollars in
the first quarter, a year-on-year rise of 16.2 percent. Exports
were worth 17.6 billion US dollars, a 20 percent increase, and
imports, 11.72 billion US dollars, a 10.7 percent increase, both
figures above the national average.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong is China's number one foreign trader and accounts for
40 percent of the country's trade. Market analysts here say that
its growth indicates that the Asian financial crisis has had no
serious effect here, but add that they need to keep their thinking
clear and work out ways to deal with any eventualities.
</P>
<P>
They say that sound economic growth in Guangdong's major
trading partners like Hong Kong, Taiwan, the United States, and
the EU has helped guarantee trade growth. But, diverse products,
product quality, and high-tech products are also important.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured goods account for as much as 94 percent of
Guangdong's exports, and more than 300 items are worth 10 million
US dollars each. Most of these are labor-intensive and
low-value-added products, however, so it is important for
Guangdong to improve its technology and create more name-brand
products, experts say.
</P>
<P>
They suggest that Guangdong keep up with international trend in
high-tech development and take advantage of the stability of the
renminbi to direct foreign capital into the capital-intensive,
high-tech enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Because China's general tariff level has dropped to around 17
percent and may go down still more, Guangdong could have certain
advantages in foreign trade, they say. Foreign trade is expected
to grow by 10 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
