<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Head of Pope's Guards Killed by Fellow Soldier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The new commander of the Swiss Guards
for Pope John Paul II was shot to death by a young fellow soldier,
the Vatican's chief spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commandant Alois Estermann, a 43-year-old Swiss national, was
found dead with his wife in their home on Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
He had been appointed just 10 hours earlier to head the elite
100-member guards that has protected successive popes for nearly
500 years.
</P>
<P>
The gunman was vice-corporal Cedric Tornay, 23. He shot the
couple and then himself with his duty-issue pistol, Navarro-Valls
told reporters in a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Tornay had stayed away one whole night from the barracks in
February and was given a written warning by Estermann, who was
then deputy commandant of the Swiss Guard.
</P>
<P>
The vice-corporal was also left off a list of Swiss Guards to
be honored by the Pope in a ceremony scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It was a fit of madness in a person with very peculiar
psychological characteristics," Navarro-Valls said.
</P>
<P>
It is reportedly also the first violent death at the Vatican in
living memory.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1506, the Swiss Guards are the world's smallest army
and one of the most colorful.
</P>
<P>
On May 6, 1527, 147 of them were killed in St. Peter's Square
protecting Pope Clement VII during the sack of Rome by the forces
of Emperor Charles V.
</P>
<P>
From then on, the Popes have preferred to have only the Swiss
nationals only to guard the Vatican. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0287 </DOCNO>
