<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Searching For 700-Year-Old Sea Battle Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese underwater archaeologists
are going to start looking for any remains of more than 1,000
warships of the Southern Song Dynasty (1127-1279) that were sunk
by Kublai Khan's army some 700 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The search will take place in Yinzhou Lake, in the city of
Xinhui in Guangdong Province, in the southern part of China. The
lake was part of the Yamen Sea where the epic battle between the
Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368) and Southern Song took place in 1279.
</P>
<P>
"Searching for the wreckage will be part of our work for the
next decade," says Zhang Wei, the director of the underwater
archaeology department of Beijing's National Museum of Chinese
History.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, Chinese archaeologists have been
cooperating with oceanographers to determine the location of the
sunken ships in the lake and have taken a piece of wood from a
ship in one of the locations and have found that it dates back to
the time of the battle.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the Mongols, led by Kublai
Khan, invaded China and drove the imperial court of the Southern
Song Dynasty to the southern part of the mainland in 1277.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Song Dynasty built a fleet of some 2,000 warships
that patrolled the sea area near the present-day cities of Xinhui
and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
In 1279, however, the fleet was attacked by the Yuan army and
only about 800 of the warships escaped. A minister of the Southern
Song, with the young emperor on his back, then jumped into the sea
to commit suicide, and the dynasty was finished.
</P>
<P>
According to scholars, most of the sea area where the battle
was fought has become dry land over the past 700 years, leaving
only the lake, where pieces of pottery, porcelain, and boards of
ships are frequently found.
</P>
<P>
This has suggested that some of the sunken warships may be
buried on land but others may remain at the bottom of the lake,
says Yu Weichao, a prominent archaeologist and former curator of
the National Museum of Chinese History.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serbia Invites Ethnic Albanians to Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Yugoslav Serbian government
Tuesday extended an invitation to leaders of ethnic Albanians in
the Serbian province of Kosovo to discuss the worsening situation
there.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government proposed that the talks be held in
Pristina, Kosovo, next Tuesday and focused on the major issues of
the autonomous status of Kosovo and the drafting of a law on local
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The Tanjug news agency reported that the invitation was issued
by Deputy Prime Minister Danilo Markovic.
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government has decided to solve all problems
concerning ethnic Albanians and other ethnic minorities through
talks in line with existing international norms, Tanjug quoted
government officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic Albanians demand the presence of international
mediators in negotiations whereas the Serbian government regards
the issue of Kosovo as an internal affair and rejects any foreign
intervention.
</P>
<P>
In a referendum conducted on April 23, 95 percent of the
Serbian citizens opposed the involvement of a third party in the
Kosovo affair.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, the Albanian foreign ministry issued a
communique, accusing Serbia of carrying out a "scorched earth
policy" in Kosovo and concentrating heavy forces in areas that
border Albania.
</P>
<P>
"Serbian paramilitary and police continue to conduct military
mopping-up operations in Kosovo, which resulted in casualties to
ethnic Albanians," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
It said Albania will maintain close cooperation with the
international community in finding a peaceful and lasting solution
to the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
