<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 140 Cambodian Refugees in Thailand Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 140 Cambodian refugees were
voluntarily repatriated Tuesday, the newspaper The Bangkok Post
Wednesday quoted the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thai Army Commander-in-Chief Chettha Thanajaro said
his country is ready to repatriate all of the nearly 100,000
refugees on its soil.
</P>
<P>
He added that the repatriation is being planned at the request
of the Cambodian government, which wants its citizens to
participate in the general election polls scheduled for July 26.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR said the 140 refugees repatriated Tuesday include 81
men and 59 women from 71 families.
</P>
<P>
So far, as many as 3,877 Cambodian refugees have been sent home
under the UNHCR's Selective Voluntary Repatriation Program, which
began last October.
</P>
<P>
Some 25,000 more Cambodian refugees crossed into Thailand since
last Friday to escape fighting between Cambodian government forces
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Two makeshift camps have been set up about eight kilometers
inside Thai territory to shelter the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another 30,000 refugees were reportedly moving close
to the Thai-Cambodian border and ready to flee into Thailand if
the situation in Cambodia deteriorates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
