<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees Fewer Tourist Arrivals Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign tourists arriving in
Thailand in the first three months of this year increased by only
2.98 percent over a year earlier, according to figures released by
the Tourism Authority of Thailand available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourist arrivals from January to March totaled 1.99
million, in contrast with the encouraging figures for January,
when arrivals went up by 13.6 percent compared with January 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government and the private sector have been counting
on tourism for an economic recovery. The Amazing Thailand 1998-99
campaign aims to achieve a 5.4-percent growth in tourist arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from East Asia, the key tourist market for Thailand,
were 4.6 percent lower in the first quarter compared with the same
period last year, with those from crisis-hit South Korea dropping
80.59 percent and Indonesia 58.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Asian decline was however offset somewhat by encouraging
growth from European markets, from where arrivals rose 14.54
percent to 619,520. Tourist arrivals from the Middle East were up
34.78 percent to 32,698.
</P>
<P>
East Asian arrivals totaled 1.04 million, with 264,009 from
Japan, 191,836 from Malaysia and 122,539 from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Growth was healthy from Hong Kong, with shoppers swelling
arrivals by 31.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
