<HEADLINE> Mexico Forest Fire Death Toll Up to 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The official death toll caused
by the forest fire in the northern mountain chain in the Mexican
state of Puebla has risen to 17, the secretary of the Puebla
government, Carlos Meza Viveros, said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The forest fire broke out on May 1, and was spread quickly by
the wind.
</P>
<P>
It caught its first victims in the "Hornos Viejos" gorge, in
"Xaltepaxco" town, where nine people found themselves surrounded
by the flames when trying to escape into a nearby cave, said state
authorities.
</P>
<P>
The army, brigades from the Ministry of Environment, Natural
Resources and Fishing and volunteers participated in the struggle
against the fire.
</P>
<P>
The fire was brought under control about 5 a.m. Tuesday local
time. More than 500 people were evacuated from the region and
taken temporarily to nearby shelters in Puebla, about 130 km away
from Mexico city. 
</P>
