<HEADLINE> Air Fares in Indonesia Raised by 37 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
approved an Indonesian National Air Carriers Association (INACA)
proposal for a 37-percent increase in air fares, following a steep
hike in fuel prices, an INACA official said.
</P>
<P>
The rise would come into effect on Wednesday and would be
applied to economy class on domestic flights only, the
association's chairman, Soelarto Hadisoemarto, said here Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The government announced Monday that fuel prices would go up by
between 25 and 71.43 percent as of Tuesday to reduce subsidies and
curb the state budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Soelarto said the air fares increase was in line with a regular
 tariff adjustment made every six months by the association as a
result of the rupiah's fluctuation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
INACA hiked air fares in December last year to adjust to the
sharp appreciation of the U.S. dollar against the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has dropped to 8,000 per dollar from 2,500 per
dollar last July.  
</P>
