<HEADLINE> Album on Yarlung Zangbo River Canyon Published in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, May 6 (Xinhua) -- An album of photos on the world's
deepest Yarlung Zangbo River Canyon in Tibet has recently been
published.
</P>
<P>
The album, published by the Petrel Publishing House in central
China, contains 525 photos and a 600,000-character description of
the canyon's beauty, geology, weather, glaciers, snow-covered
mountains, rare plants and wild animals, giving readers a
complete picture of this natural wonder.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists have conducted a series of research in the
canyon since the early 1970s and have gathered a great number of
materials and data on the 500-km-long canyon.
</P>
<P>
The canyon is formed by a sudden bend of the 2,058-km Yarlung
Zangbo River. The river starts in southwestern Tibet, travels
eastwards along the Himalayas, and suddenly changes its course
southwards in southeastern Tibet, before it flows out of China and
eventually empties into the Bay of Bengal.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Petrel Publishing House said that the photos
were taken by Chinese Academy of Sciences researchers who have a
total of 20 years of experience doing scientific surveys in the
canyon area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
