<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiny Baby Leaves Hospital Safe and Sound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A baby, considered the tiniest
to survive in the U.S. state of Oregon, went home from hospital
last week in apparent good health, the Oregonain reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
When William Steven Hunnicutt was born 13 weeks prematurely, he
weighed only 12.7 ounces (0.360 kilogram) and was nine inches
(about 22.86 centimeters) in length. The baby's diminutive size
made him a giant challenge for doctors.
</P>
<P>
At the gestational age of 27 weeks, William was in a life-and-death
situation for his parents to make a decision: Continue to stay in his
mother's womb and hope for the best, or be brought into the world by
surgeons and rely on medical technology to keep him alive.
</P>
<P>
At 27 weeks' gestation, an infant of normal weight -- about two
pounds four ounces (about 1.024 kilograms) -- has a 90 percent
chance of living if sophisticated medical treatment is available,
doctors say. But studies of infants born weighing less than 17.5
ounces (about 0.497 kilogram) indicate a 20 percent probability of
survival.
</P>
<P>
For William to survive, doctors had to place a tube down his
throat to connect his lungs to a ventilator that would breathe for
him. And they had to thread catheters into the major vein and
artery in his umbilical cord. The catheters allow doctors to give
intravenous fluids and medications and to take blood samples.
</P>
<P>
The neonatal intensive care unit, where the baby spent 111
days, was equipped with the smallest of everything -- the tiniest
catheters, needles, measuring devices.
</P>
<P>
The doctors say that the baby has avoided many of the worse
ailments that can befall a premature child. He didn't have a brain
hemorrhage. His lungs and intestines are well developed. He has
some retinopathy but appears to be minor. He had no seizures after
birth -- a sign that he could have escaped serious neurological
problems that often afflict premature children.
</P>
<P>
Now at home, the baby relies on supplemental oxygen for his
tiny lungs.
</P>
<P>
Since birth, he has bulked up to four pounds (about 1.816
kilograms) and has grown in length to 16 inches (about 40.64
centimeters).
</P>
<P>
Doctors say it's too early to tell whether William will suffer
long-term disabilities. Extremely small babies are at risk for
neurological impairment such as cerebral palsy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
