<HEADLINE> Philippine Agents Find Bugs in Estrada Aide's Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 6 (Xinhua) -- Agents of the Philippine Presidential
Anti-Crime Commission have found phone-tapping devices in the
former office of an aide of leading opposition presidential
candidate Joseph Estrada.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Manila Standard Wednesday quoted senior
superintendent Eduardo Matillano as saying the defunct office was
used as a "listening post" by Estrada, the standard bearer of the
opposition Laban ng Makabayang Masang Pilipino (the Fight of
Patriotic Filipino Masses).
</P>
<P>
The bugs were found in a raid conducted by Matillano's men on
Tuesday. Matillano said they could not identify at the moment the
ruling party's candidates allegedly being monitored from the
listening post.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Jose de Venecia, the anointed presidential
candidate of the ruling party by President Fidel Ramos, has been
trailing Estrada in all popularity surveys.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the finding of bugs, media bureau chief
Rodlfo Reyes of Estrada's party said whatever evidence the agents
found there "was planted to stop the inevitable victory of
Estrada." 
</P>
