<HEADLINE> No Troops to Kosovo, Italian Defense Minister Stresses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Military interference could not solve
the problems in the Serbian province of Kosovo and no one had the
intention of sending troops to that region, Italian Defense
Minister Beniamino Andreatta told reporters here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The six countries in the contact group on former Yugoslav are
coordinating their stands and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is also exchanging views on this question, he
said.
</P>
<P>
But none intended sending troops there because it was not
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"We hope all parties concerned in that question can sit down
with no preconditions to evaluate the situation facing them," the
defense minister said.
</P>
<P>
Tension in the Serbian province of Kosovo has heightened since
the end of February when Serb police clashed with ethnic Albanians
who make up 90 percent of the 1.9 million population and were
seeking independence from Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
