<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Officials Suspended for Links with Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman
on Tuesday suspended four high ranking officials from their duties
for their alleged involvement in a drug-trafficking case.
</P>
<P>
The officials were Mario Rivas, director of civil aeronautics,
Carlos Garcia Solorzano, general director of migration and foreign
affairs, Carlos Palacio Linarte, anti-drug police chief, and
Carlos Bendana, who was the link with the interpol.
</P>
<P>
According to police investigations, an airplane, Jet Lear 35a,
was stolen on December 15, 1997, in Florida, the United States,
and flown into Nicaragua on December 24, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft was later used by a Cuban American citizen,
identified as Jorge Guasch, to transport cocaine from South
America to the United States.
</P>
<P>
To avoid being inspected, the drug dealer devoted 10 flight
hours for trips of the president and some other high ranking
government officials.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the decision to suspend the four officials at a
press conference here, President Aleman said, "the executive power
is obliged to look after the compliance with the law, national
security and public morals."
</P>
<P>
He admitted having traveled once by the aircraft when attending
a presidential summit in Central America on February 4.
</P>
<P>
However, he denied local press reports which named him "mulero"
(person who transports an article or illicit product) of the drug
dealer and accused him of taking narcotics to the atlantic coast
of the country.
</P>
<P>
The president demanded his innocence in this case, saying that
this sole trip in the aircraft had a very strong security and
military custody.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three commissions have been formed to continue
investigations into the "Jet Lear 35a case" and they are required
to present their conclusions to the president within a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Names Mutombo Defensive Player of Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Basketball
Association (NBA) on Tuesday announced that Atlanta Hawks center
Dikembe Mutombo became the Defensive Player of Year, edging
Seattle SuperSonics guard Gary Payton by just two votes.
</P>
<P>
Mutombo was the first player to win the NBA's Defensive Player
of the Year award three times. He first won the award with the
Denver Nuggets in 1994-95 before Payton interrupted his run in
1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Mutombo received 39 of a possible 116 votes from a panel of
media representatives throughout the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
San Antonio center David Robinson, who returned from an
injury-plagued season to help the Spurs post the best scoring
defense in the league, was a distant third with 10 votes and
Michael Jordan of the Chicago Bulls was fourth with six
votes. Both are former winners of the defensive award.
</P>
<P>
Mutombo, a native of Zaire, helped the Hawks to a 50-32 record
and was second in the NBA with 3.38 blocked shots per game this
season. He recorded at least six rejections in 16 different
games, had five or more on 23 occasions and finished with four or
more in 32 contests.
</P>
<P>
On the final day of the season, Mutombo recorded his 2,027th
career block, matching Larry Nance for the 10th-best total in
league history, despite playing only six seasons.
</P>
<P>
Mutombo played in all 82 games this season and averaged 13.4
points and 11.4 rebounds, shooting 53.7 percent (399-for- 743)
from the field. He was third in the NBA in rebounding and sixth in
shooting percentage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
