<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Securities Industry Association of the United
States signed an agreement with the self-regulatory organization
of Russia's securities industry here Tuesday to enhance their
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The SIA and the National Association of the Securities Market
Participants of Russia intend to cooperate in developing training
and continuing education programs for the management and employees
of member firms of both organizations. (US-Russia-Securities)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair will fly to
Northern Ireland Wednesday to urge the electorate to give a huge
"yes" vote in the referendum on the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
He will share a platform with the architect of the agreement,
former Conservative government Prime Minister John Major.
(UK-N.Ireland-Blair)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A group of seven former U.S. defense secretaries
urged Congress to fund the multi-billion dollar F-22 project
despite problems, fearing that a replaced fighter project would
drag the United States behind other nations, the United Press
International said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The F-22 project should be continued because it was a superior
airplane and also because it would take years for the Air Force to
design and build a new stealth fighter from scratch, the defense
chiefs said. (US-F-22)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Palestinian President Yasser Arafat said here Tuesday
afternoon that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had made
some progress at the two-day London talks aimed at reviving the
deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a brief meeting with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, Arafat gave his verdict to the crucial Middle
East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot say that the London talks failed. I have heard from
Madame Albright that there was some progress and that time is
needed," Arafat said. (UK-Arafat-London Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said here
Tuesday that the three-way peace talks in London made some
progress, but some problems remain unresolved.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said, "There has been progress, even significant
progress in some of the areas." But he also stressed: "We have
not closed all the gaps and we are working and going to be working
in the next few days to see if we can resolve some of the needed,"
Arafat said. (UK-Arafat-London Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran Tuesday once again rejected Argentina's
accusation that Tehran was involved in the 1994 bomb attack on a
Jewish center in Buenos Aires, Iran's official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi dismissed
as "baseless" the recent charge raised by Argentine prosecutor
Eamon Mullen that the then Iranian cultural attache to Argentina
had been involved in the bomb attack which killed 88 people and
injured 159 others. (Iran-Argentina-Bomb)  
</P>
