<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United States Names 20 to World Cup Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Soccer National Team head
coach Steve Sampson on Tuesday named 20 of his 22-man roster for
the 1998 World Cup finals in France, with some players to make
their third World Cup appearance.
</P>
<P>
The roster includes 12 players from the 1994 World Cup team and
six players from the Atlanta Olympics squad beside two, Marcelo
Balboa and Eric Wynalda, who will play their third World Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
Sampson said he intended to fill the final two spots with
midfielder Tab Ramos and defender David Regis. Both players will
be evaluated during the team's three weeks together before
departing to France June 4.
</P>
<P>
"I believe we can do something special at this World Cup. I
would not put it beyond this team to get to the third round," said
Sampson in a teleconference call.
</P>
<P>
The official roster will not be submitted until the FIFA
deadline of June 2, he said.
</P>
<P>
Missing from the squad is former captain John Harkes, a veteran
of the last two World Cups, dropped by Sampson two weeks ago
because of poor play and attitude.
</P>
<P>
The move surprised several members of the American team, and
displayed the seriousness of Sampson's approach to the World Cup.
He named Thomas Dooley, who turns 37 on may 12, as the new
captain.
</P>
<P>
Striker Roy Lassiter was also not included, with Sampson citing
his poor recent form in Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
The team's average age is 28 and the average number of
international appearances is 51.
</P>
<P>
The United States finished 14th in the U.S.-hosted 1994 World
Cup and expectations are high to improve on that performance in
France. The U.S. team will play its opening World Cup match June
15 against three-time champions Germany in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Six days later, the Americans will face Iran in Lyon, and will
play Yugoslavia on June 25 in Nantes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
