Juninho, who has just recovered from a broken leg, lost his place
in Brazil's squad to Barcelona's Giovanni when defending champions
announced their World Cup roster on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Juninho has returned to fitness quickly after breaking his
leg in February but coach Zagallo decided to use an in-form
Giovanni instead of him.
</P>
<P>
There came a surprise when Zagallo even named his starting
line-up for Brazil's opening World Cup match against Scotland in
Paris on June 10.
</P>
<P>
Taffarel, Cafu, Aldair, Junior Baiano, Roberto Carlos, Dunga,
Cesar Sampaio, Rivaldo, Giovanni, Romario and Ronaldo were the 11
picked for the first game of Brazil's campaign to win a fifth
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Sao Paulo midfielder Denilson, a regular over the last year,
was surprisingly omitted.
</P>
<P>
The only other surprise was the inclusion in the squad of
central defender Marcio Santos, a survivor from the 1994 World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
Paris St Germain midfielder Rai, who was recalled after a
four-year absence for last week's friendly against Argentina, was
excluded, while Fiorentina's Edmundo, who has suffered from a
suspect temperament this year, was included.
</P>
