<HEADLINE> Moldovan Communists to Back Resigned Premier for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The Communist group, the only
opposition in the new Moldovan parliament, will back Ion Ciubuc,
the resigned premier, for a new term in the office of premier if
he is proposed by the president of the republic.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by secretary of the party Andrei Neguta
as reported Tuesday by the Moldovan news press BASA-PRESS.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Convention is due to advance its candidate and
the other alliance members must respect this choice, under the
agreement of foundation of the parliamentary majority -- the
Alliance for Democracy and Reforms which is composed of the
Democratic Convention, the Democratic and Prosperous Moldova Bloc
and the Party of Democratic Forces.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Neguta said that Valentin Dolganiuc, nominee of the
Democratic Convention, "does not have all necessary qualities for
taking the premiership." The communists will take its final
attitude on the issue of government after it is informed of the
program and membership of the new cabinet, he added.
</P>
<P>
Legislators from the majority Alliance for Democracy and
Reforms decline from commenting on the subject unless guaranteed
the anonymity. Many of them describe Dolganiuc as "lacking
experience."
</P>
<P>
Dolganiuc's supporters, however, affirm that reservations
shared by a part of deputies, including members of the coalition,
"might have had another origin: unwillingness to allow a person
who is far from a particular nomenclature or influent circles to
hold a key post."
</P>
<P>
President Petre Luchinsky had consultations Monday and Tuesday
with Alliance and Communist leaders to highlight a nominee for
prime ministership.
</P>
<P>
The prerogative to move a candidature for the post of premier
belongs to the head of state, according to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The government headed by Ion Ciubuc resigned last Thursday
after 15 months of work. Petre Luchinsky had said earlier that he
would like to see Ion Ciubuc in the position of the premier.
</P>
</TEXT>
