<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Pull Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street pulled back
from its record high Tuesday, as investors are again worried about
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell almost exactly as much as
it rose in setting a record Monday, slipping 45.09 points to
9,147.57.
</P>
<P>
Broader indexes also extended Monday's late pullback.
</P>
<P>
Stocks were pressured throughout the session by a weak bond
market, where the yield on the 30-year Treasury rose back toward 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Bonds struggled after a top official at the International
Monetary Fund indicated again the possibility for the Federal
Reserve to raise interest rate to cool down the economy.
</P>
<P>
The comments quickly reopened the inflation debate that
unexpectedly flared up last week, but was seemingly resolved only
days later by a series of encouraging economic reports.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 583.63 million
shares, similar to the pace of the prior two sessions.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 6.42 to 1,115.65, and the Nasdaq
composite index fell 13.95 points to 1,864.91.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 2.98 to 579.75, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.52 to 745.28.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.72 to
481.74. 
</P>
</TEXT>
