<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Revamps Extradition Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada moved Tuesday to revamp its
ancient extradition laws in a bid to make it easier to extradite
accused criminals.
</P>
<P>
The legislation tabled by Justice Minister Anne McLellan would,
among other things, allow alleged war criminals to stand trial at
international tribunals.
</P>
<P>
Among the other planned changes to streamline the extradition
process:
</P>
<P>
-- The ground for extradition will be broadened and not limited
to a specific list of crimes set out in the act. This will allow
for extradition for new offenses, such as computer crimes;
</P>
<P>
-- More flexibility in admitting in Canadian courts different
forms of evidence in other countries;
</P>
<P>
-- New procedures to allow a fugitive to waive extradition and
voluntarily return to the other country.
</P>
<P>
The new laws will also abandon a former list of extraditable
offenses that included such outdated crimes as slave trade.
</P>
<P>
This is the first in over 120 years that Canada reforms its
extradition laws, which is expected to bring the country more in
step with other industrialized nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Opens Hearing on Flight Accident in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- There was no evidence that a U.S.
Marine pilot intentionally flew his surveillance jet under a ski
lift in Italy, killing 20 skiers in a gondola car, a U.S. military
attorney said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A week-long hearing was held in Camp LeJeune Marine Corps Base,
North Carolina, to determine whether Captains Chandler Seagraves,
28, and William Raney II, 26, should be court-martialed for the
accident, which took place in February at ski resorts near the
Aviano, Italy, air base.
</P>
<P>
In opening arguments, Marine Captain Paul Kaplan disputed
prosecutors' allegations that there was a "cable car club" that
crewmen could join by making a dangerous pass under a lift cable.
</P>
<P>
"The evidence simply will not support such a wild theory," said
Kaplan, a military attorney for Seagraves.
</P>
<P>
Later this week, a military judge will consider whether
Seagraves and Raney should be court-martialed on 20 counts each of
involuntary manslaughter and negligent homicide.
</P>
<P>
Seagraves and Raney sat at the rear seats when the accident
occurred.
</P>
<P>
The jet's pilot, Captain Richard J. Ashby, 30, of Mission
Viejo, California, and navigator Captain Joseph Schweitzer, 30, of
Westbury, New York, will face a similar hearing in June.
</P>
<P>
Captain Michael Recce, the first prosecution witness and
squadron duty officer on the day of the mishap, said the ski lift
was not on U.S. military maps of the region.
</P>
<P>
A military report said there were standing orders to maintain a
minimum altitude of 610 meters and a maximum airspeed of 450 knots
on low-level training flights.
</P>
<P>
However, the jet clipped the cables suspended between 111 and
113 meters off the ground and reached speeds of up to 555 knots
during the flight.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Population Migrates From Town to Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bucharest, May 5 (Xinhua) -- The urban-to-rural migration tide
is preponderant in Romanian internal migration, the state news
agency Rompres Tuesday cited the National Statistics Commission as
saying.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time since the 1968 administrative division
that in 1997 the population in urban areas registered a negative
residence changing migration balance, which had been ascertained
in over two thirds of the all 41 county capitals and Bucharest,
the same source said. In the past year, the rate of internal
migration was 13.4 persons per 1,000 inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
According to the same source, the negative balance in the urban
areas was due, within the population structure by age, to the
inhabitants of 34 years old and over, in the sense that the
percent of the departures exceeded the arrivals one.
</P>
<P>
Among the main reasons to the urban-to-rural migration tide are
the high rate of unemployment in the urban areas and the process
of land privatization in the countryside, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
It is worth noticing that out of a total number of persons
changing their residence last year, only an 11.1 percent declared
as a reason the change of working place, while the rest of them
claimed family problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Student Gets Prison Term for E-Mail Hate Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A former University of
California student became the first person in the United States to
be sentenced to prison for committing a federal hate crime over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. district court in Santa Ana, California, Monday
sentenced Richard Machado to one-year imprisonment. He was
convicted in February of violating the civil rights of 59 Asian
students at UC-Irvine to whom he sent threatening e-mail in 1996.
</P>
<P>
With credit for time served in custody, Machado, 21, is free on
conditions including one year on federal probation, a 1,000-dollar
fine and mandatory psychiatric counseling.
</P>
<P>
In his e-mail message, signed "Asian Hater," he warned that all
Asians should leave campus or the sender would "hunt all of you
down and kill your stupid asses."
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers had portrayed the former student as a bored and
troubled teenager who sent the message as a prank.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors countered with testimony from students who said
they were terrified by Machado's message. Machado told police then
that there were too many Asian students at Irvine, and that they
studied too hard and threatened his own ability to succeed. Asian
students account for 58 percent of UC-Irvine's undergraduate
population, the highest proportion on any UC campus.
</P>
<P>
One of the attorneys who prosecuted Machado's case praised the
sentence as a victory for federal authorities seeking to crack
down on hate crimes in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Attorney's Office in Los Angeles district is
investigating a new case involving a student at California State
University's Los Angeles campus who allegedly sent an anti-Latino
e-mail message to professors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
