<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair, Major to Tour N.Ireland for "Yes" Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
will fly to Northern Ireland Wednesday to urge the electorate to
give a huge "yes" vote in the referendum on the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
He will share a platform with the architect of the agreement,
former Conservative government Prime Minister John Major, BBC
ceefax news reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The current major opposition Conservative Party leader William
Hague and the third largest Liberal Democratic Party leader Paddy
Ashdown will also tour the divided province soon to boost the
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The historic peace agreement was struck on April 10 by eight
major political parties in Northern Ireland with sponsorship of
the British and Irish governments. A referendum will be held
concurrently in Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic on May 22
to decide on the fate of the peace deal.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's 60 percent Protestant majority is split over
the peace accord, although opinion polls show the majority are
supportive to the deal on both Northern Ireland and the Irish
Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Airlines Vie for Asian Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's largest carrier Air Canada
is pushing hard to get unlimited access to Asian destinations and
compete freely with rival Canadian Airlines on its home turf.
</P>
<P>
The move comes as Canadian Transport Minister David Collenette
begins a review of air policy, and Canadian Airlines is in better
shape after a restructuring last year.
</P>
<P>
Air Canada, which has traditionally focused its international
traffic on Europe, is prevented from expanding its Asian business
by a federal policy intended to protect Canadian Airlines'
traditional dominance there.
</P>
<P>
At present, the carrier is not allowed to fly to any Japanese
city other than Osaka, and is limited to four flights a week to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, demand for flights to Asia is booming beyond
Canadian Airlines' ability to meet it.
</P>
<P>
"When we can't fly directly to foreign climes, that traffic
gets diverted to U.S. hubs, and Toronto, Vancouver and Montreal
lose jobs," said Geoffrey Elliot, Air Canada's senior vice
president of corporate affairs.
</P>
<P>
"It's not just Air Canada pays the price, the whole economy
pays the price," Elliot noted.
</P>
<P>
It's estimated that every new daily route to Asia can create
950 direct and indirect jobs for the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Air Canada is pushing the government to forge
Open Skies deals with countries other than the United States.
</P>
<P>
Canada should move quickly while the United States is forging
aggressively ahead with multilateral treaties giving its carriers
free access to the world, it argued.
</P>
<P>
The recent U.S.- Japanese Open Skies Pact paves the way for 90
new flights a week between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980506.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-05-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Former Defense Chiefs Call for Continued F-22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 5 (Xinhua) -- A group of seven former U.S.
defense secretaries urged Congress to fund the multi-billion
dollar F-22 project despite problems, fearing that a replaced
fighter project would drag the United States behind other nations,
the United Press International said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The F-22 project should be continued because it was a superior
airplane and also because it would take years for the Air Force to
design and build a new stealth fighter from scratch, the defense
chiefs said.
</P>
<P>
Such a delay would allow other nations, several of which are
already in the advanced stages of developing new stealth fighters,
to start adding aircraft that are superior to current U.S.
military planes to their air forces, the secretaries warned in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued through the Alexis de Tocqueville
Institution, a think tank that specializes in defense-related
issues.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed by Casper Weinberger, William Perry,
Frank Carlucci, Richard Cheney, James Schlesinger, Donald
Rumsfeld, and Harold Brown, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
